column37: High winds began in the Santa Ana Mountains between 0630 and 0730 PST and continued through 1130 PST. Between 0830 PST and 0930 PST, a peak wind gust of 70 MPH was measured by the Fremont Canyon RAWS.
column38: Another round of Santa Ana winds occurred on March 27th as high pressure built in over the Great Basin. No wind damage was reported during this event.

column37: Wind gusts in excess of 58 MPH were measured by the Julian mesonet between 1114 and 1334 PST. Multiple gusts of 61 MPH were measured 1313 and 1334 PST.
column38: An upper level trough of low pressure brought light to moderate showers and gusty winds on April 4th and 5th. Rainfall amounts in the coastal and valley locations were generally less than one-quarter inch, while the more favorable locations along the SW facing slopes of the San Bernardino Mountains received almost 1.5 inches. Winds were the main concern with this system, mainly in the mountains and deserts. Wind gusts up to 76 MPH were measured in Lucerne Valley.

The Camp Pendleton Fire began at approximately 0823 PST on July 13th at the Camp Pendleton Marine Base, California. The fire started due to training exercises at the base on the southwest range. No structures were damages and no injuries occurred. The fire grew to 3500+ acres before being contained around 1700 PST on the 14th.

column37: A short, but intense thunderstorm near Borrego Springs caused runoff from heavy rain to enter some stores in town as well as a roof torn off due to gusty winds.
column38: A weak easterly wave brought widespread showers and thunderstorms to Southern California with mostly light to moderate rainfall, but heavy in spots. Easterly flow also helped to bring the rainfall to the coast. Very heavy rainfall and gusty winds were reported in San Diego, Riverside and San Bernardino Counties.

column37: The Mataguaty SDGE anemometer, located at 6 meters above ground level, measured a peak wind at 1230 PST out of the NNW at 30 MPH with a gust of 60 MPH.  Downdrafts in excess of 40 MPH began shortly after 1220 and continued until 1250 PDT.
column38: Moist and unstable monsoonal flow triggered scattered showers and thunderstorms across San Diego, San Bernardino and Riverside Counties, a few of which reached severe status with large hail and damaging winds. Localized flash flooding was also reported in a few locations over the 2-day event.

The Long Canyon fire started around 1100 PST on September 23rd in the Cleveland National Forest in eastern Orange County, west of the Ortega Highway near the Riverside County line. Some structures were threatened, but the fire generally burned away from the populated areas, 40 acres total. Three firefighters and one police officer suffered non-life threatening heat-related and smoke inhalation injuries. One of the Cleveland National Forest's fire engines was destroyed by fire, cause unknown, no injuries.

column37: High winds began at Mt. Laguna between 0650 and 0750 PST. A peak gust of 77 MPH was measured by the Mt. Laguna Mesonet. High winds ended between 0950 and 1050 PST.
column38: Strong westerly (onshore) flow brought gusty winds to the mountains and deserts of southern California on October 25. The winds caused a few areas of blowing dust and local power outages.

column37: High winds began in the Santa Ana mountain foothills between 0530 and 0630 PST and continued to between 0930 and 1030 PST. Between 0820 and 0920 PST, multiple gusts above 58 MPH occurred. A peak wind gust of 61 MPH was measured by the Fremont Canyon RAWS.
column38: Strong offshore flow, set up by strong high pressure in the Great Basin and a thermal Low off the California coast, caused strong winds in the Inland Empire, downing tree limbs and knocking out power to thousands of customers.

column37: High winds began at the Fremont Canyon RAWS between 0830 and 0930 PST, during which time a peak gust of 74 MPH was measured. High winds ended between 1730 and 1830 PST.
column38: A high pressure ridge built along the west coast, along with high pressure building over the great basin, set up a pattern favorable for moderate to strong Santa Ana winds across southwest California.

column37: High winds began at the Fremont Canyon RAWS between 0230 and 0330 PST, during which time a peak gust of 64 MPH was measured by the spotter. High winds ended between 0530 and 0630 PST.
column38: North to Northeast winds behind a trough of low pressure over Arizona and surface high pressure over the Great Basin brought moderate to locally strong offshore winds through and below canyons and mountain passes.

column37: High winds began in Boulder Creek between 0720 and 0730 PST, during which time a peak gust of 58 MPH was measured by the SDGE mesonet station. High winds ended between 0750 and 0800 PST.
column38: North to Northeast winds behind a trough of low pressure over Arizona and surface high pressure over the Great Basin brought moderate to locally strong offshore winds through and below canyons and mountain passes.

column37: Wind gusts estimated around 58 MPH were blamed for toppling a large Eucalyptus tree onto several parked vehicles in La Jolla. No one was injured. A semi was also blown over, blocking two lanes of eastbound Interstate 8 at Route 79. Again, no injuries. A downed power line near Ramona cause power outages to around 200 customers.
column38: A strong cold upper level low pressure system moved southward from the Four Corners region into northern Mexico. Strong surface high pressure settled over the Great Basin and helped to bring strong offshore winds from the 2nd through the 4th of the month. The strongest winds occurred in and below the canyons and passes, causing downed trees and power lines.

column37: San Diego County Flood Control reported 0.80 inches of rain over 15 minutes and an additional 0.10 inches over the next 5 minutes, resulting in 0.90 inches of rain over 20 minutes.
column38: Strong high pressure aloft was centered over the four corners area of the southwest, which resulted in monsoonal flow into the region from the 4th through the 8th. Precipitable water values around two inches supported heavy rainfall from thunderstorms in the mountains and deserts. The most intense thunderstorms occurred on the 6th, when a few severe storms roamed the Inland Empire with strong winds and hail. Flash flooding was observed near Wrightwood and Phelan, while the Whitewater River north of Whitewater experienced a rapid rise in flow.

The Eagle fire started around 0940 PST on July 21, off Eagles Nest Road and Camino San Ignacio, roughly five miles east of Warner Springs. Only one outbuilding was destroyed, and the fire generally burned in unpopulated areas to a total size of 14,140 acres. Eighteen fire personnel suffered non-life threatening injuries. The cause of the fire was determined to be arson. Lost Valley Boy Scout Camp and the Borrego Palm Canyon Campground were evacuated while the fire was battled and reopened soon after the fire was fully contained on Saturday the 23rd.

column37: Anza-Borrego State Park rangers reported three power poles down due to thudnerstorm wind gusts.
column38: Strong high pressure aloft over the southwest U.S. produced a monsoonal flow over much of California, resulting in periods of showers and thunderstorms, mainly in the mountains and deserts. An upper atmospheric disturbance produced widespread showers and a few thunderstorms with moderate rainfall over northern portions of the area overnight on the 30th into the early morning of the 31st. A few of the storms were quite heavy to locally severe during the afternoons of the 30th and 31st. Many of the strongest storms occurred over rural mountain and desert areas where verification was difficult. Flash Flooding was reported in the Victorville area of the northern deserts on the 30th, along with some wind damage. The nocturnal event on the night of the 30th produced several hundred lightning cloud to ground lightning strikes.

column37: The SDGE Mesonet, CMCSD recorded a wind gust of 65 mph during a downburst from a thunderstorm at 1400 PST on the 28th. The Campo ASOS also recorded a gust of 61 mph at 1352 PST nearby. During the time of these gusts, 5 power poles were snapped on Buckman Springs Road near Highway 94 and several large tree branches fell onto the Campo COOP observer's property. Power was lost soon after these poles and branches came down. Lightning sparked several small fires on the observer's property, but all were contained quickly. The Campo ASOS also recorded 1.02 inches of rain in 30 minutes during this storm.
column38: A surge of monsoonal moisture brought three days of significant thunderstorms from the 26th to the 28th. These storms brought more CG lightning, strong wind gusts in the low 50s mph, 1/2-3/4 hail and brief heavy downpours. Minor accumulation from small hail occurred with some of these storms. The rain produced some flash flooding at low water crossings in Chihuahua Valley. Street flooding and 1/2 hail was also reported near Big Bear in the San Bernardino Mountains. Lightning sparked several small fires in the Riverside and San Bernardino County mountains, including one that became the Oasis Fire.

The Great fire started around 1153 PST on the 1st, on the south side of Highway 78 at Scissors Crossing, near Shelter Valley. During the firefight, Highway 78 between San Felipe Rd in Scissors Crossing and Wynola Rd was closed. Only one firefighter sustained minor injuries and no structures or homes were threatened or damaged. The fire burned a total of 2,135 acres before being fully contained around 0600 PST on the 6th.

column37: Strong winds began at the Harrison Park RAWS between 1400 and 1500 PST and ended between 1700 and 1800 PST. During this time, high winds were reached with a gust of 59 mph between 1610 and 1620 PST.
column38: A large upper-level low pressure system brought a strong cold front through southern California the 4th through the 6th, providing widespread moderate rain, well below normal temperatures and strong gusty winds. Most areas west of the mountains received 3/4 - 1 1/2 inches of rain, with higher amounts of 2 inches or more in the mountains and coastal slopes. This storm packed the highest rainfall totals for mountain locations like Idyllwild since 2004. Light amounts of snow were also seen at the highest elevations. Strong winds also led to downed power lines and overturned vehicles in Lucerne Valley.

column37: High winds began at the Fremont Canyon RAWS between 2230 and 2330 PST on the 1st and ended between 1030 and 1130 PST on the 2nd. During that time, a peak gust of 81 mph was measured between 0330 and 0430 PST on the 2nd.|Nearby, a large sign was blown down on the 91 freeway near Highway 55.
column38: An inside slider upper-level low pressure system, passing just north of southern California and then across the Great Basin, resulted in strong sustained and gusty northerly winds across much of the Inland Empire and Santa Ana Mountains. Several sites recorded sustained winds of 40-50 mph with gusts over 60 mph. Minor wind damage was reported with this event. A traffic light was blown down in Rancho Cucamonga and a sign blown down onto the freeway near Yorba Linda. A few small brush fires also broke out near Rincon and along the 15 freeway in San Diego County.

column37: High winds began at the Tonner Canyon RAWS between 0600 and 0700 PST on the 2nd and ended between 1100 and 1200 PST. During that time, winds gusted consistently above 50 mph with a peak gust of 60 mph measured between 1000 and 1100 PST.
column38: An inside slider upper-level low pressure system, passing just north of southern California and then across the Great Basin, resulted in strong sustained and gusty northerly winds across much of the Inland Empire and Santa Ana Mountains. Several sites recorded sustained winds of 40-50 mph with gusts over 60 mph. Minor wind damage was reported with this event. A traffic light was blown down in Rancho Cucamonga and a sign blown down onto the freeway near Yorba Linda. A few small brush fires also broke out near Rincon and along the 15 freeway in San Diego County.

column37: High winds began at the Otay Mountain SDGE mesonet site between 0910 and 0920 PST on the 10th and ended between 1030 and 1040 PST. During this time, several gusts over 58 mph were recorded with a peak gust of 63 mph measured between 0910 and 0920 PST.
column38: A strong, cut-off low pressure system dropped south along the Southern California coast and moved directly across San Diego and northern Baja, bringing 2 days of widespread moderate to heavy rainfall, along with gusty winds, mostly on the 12th. Rainfall amounts over this two-day period were substantial, with locally heavy rainfall rates, providing northern areas west of the mountains with .25 to .50 inch of rain, and one to two inches over the vast majority of San Diego County, even spilling over into the deserts. Lindbergh Field had a peak rainfall rate of 0.40 inches per hour and nearly reached their daily rainfall record with a daily total of 1.4 inches. Urban-type street flooding occurred with this system, dumping up to 1000 cfs of water into the San Diego River on the 12th.

column37: CBS 8 via Twitter reported a large tree down on power lines leaving 1500 customers without power. There were no nearby wind reports, but nearby gusts were measured around 40 mph out of the east.
column38: A strong, cut-off low pressure system dropped south along the Southern California coast and moved directly across San Diego and northern Baja, bringing 2 days of widespread moderate to heavy rainfall, along with gusty winds, mostly on the 12th. Rainfall amounts over this two-day period were substantial, with locally heavy rainfall rates, providing northern areas west of the mountains with .25 to .50 inch of rain, and one to two inches over the vast majority of San Diego County, even spilling over into the deserts. Lindbergh Field had a peak rainfall rate of 0.40 inches per hour and nearly reached their daily rainfall record with a daily total of 1.4 inches. Urban-type street flooding occurred with this system, dumping up to 1000 cfs of water into the San Diego River on the 12th.

column37: High winds began at the Boulder Creek SDGE mesonet site around 2100 PST on the 5th and ended around midnight on the 6th. During that time, several gusts over 58 mph were recorded including a peak gust of 65 mph around 2130 PST and another of 62 mph around 2300 PST.
column38: These events were the result of a large upper-level closed low over northern Baja, Mexico and featured four Santa Ana events, the strongest of which occurred in Orange County and southwest San Bernardino County with wind gusts 45 to 65+ mph and reported damage on December 1. These winds were strong enough to overturn several trucks, down power lines, reduce visibilities in dust and topple hundreds of large trees in Rancho Cucamonga (near Fontana, San Bernardino and Ontario), near the Cajon Pass along I-15. Rancho Cucamonga was declared a state of emergency by the State of California for the nearly 500 trees damaged. Overall, approximately 400 tons of debris was mitigated in the Rancho Cucamonga area.This area also suffered damage to the electrical infrastructure leaving many without power. As far as snow goes, 15 to 20 inches occurred in the San Bernardino County Mountains near Big Bear and Onyx Peak December 1 to 2, while only a dusting occurred in those mountains west of I-15. Much drier air moved into San Diego County on Saturday December 3, when the Santa Ana mountains and foothills had another surge of Santa Ana/offshore winds with gusts to near 60 mph and very low relative humidity. The final period of winds developed behind another system passing to our east on Monday, bringing wind gusts to 50 to 65 mph Monday night and Tuesday morning in the San Diego County mountains, and very low humidity.

column37: High winds began at the Fremont Canyon RAWS between 0351 and 0451 PST on the 16th and ended between 1351 and 1451 PST the same day. During that time a max gust of 65 mph was measured, along with several other gusts above 58 mph (including 2 of 61 mph and one of 60 mph).||During this time, power poles were reported down by Fox 11 News in nearby Yorba Linda. Around 240 customers were reported without power in nearby Tustin as well.
column38: This upper-level low pressure system developed right on the heels of the last and became a closed low over the Northern Baja for 2 days, drawing moisture back into the area along with strong, widespread offshore winds. This system also set off intense showers and isolated thunderstorms with pea-sized hail (accumulations in Rancho Cucamonga and Mission Viejo), as well as several funnel clouds spotted east of John Wayne Airport. Most of the rain with this system was confined to Orange County, the Inland Empire and the northern mountains. Heavy rain was observed in Orange County and the Inland Empire on the 15th and 16th with locations there recording between one-quarter and one-half inch.  The snow level dropped to around 3500 ft., with accumulations of 3 to 8 inches there. Bear Mountain resort recorded 12 to 16 inches. Strong winds were also observed with this storm, especially on the 16th, which was a more widespread wind event than early December, impacting all counties, including San Diego County, with warning-level winds. Several wind gusts of 45-65 mph were reported in the Santa Ana Mountains, the Inland Empire and San Diego County Mountains. Several trees and power poles were downed, leaving many without power.

column37: Strong winds damaged the patio roof on the property. Tree limbs as large as 4 inches in diameter have been breaking off trees. Property is located on Pala Mesa Road near SR 76 near Fallbrook.
column38: This upper-level low pressure system developed right on the heels of the last and became a closed low over the Northern Baja for 2 days, drawing moisture back into the area along with strong, widespread offshore winds. This system also set off intense showers and isolated thunderstorms with pea-sized hail (accumulations in Rancho Cucamonga and Mission Viejo), as well as several funnel clouds spotted east of John Wayne Airport. Several wind gusts of 45-65 mph were reported in the Santa Ana Mountains, the Inland Empire and San Diego County Mountains. Several trees and power poles were downed, leaving many without power.

column37: High winds began between 0551 and 0651 PST on the 22nd at the Fremont Canyon RAWS and ended between 1451 and 1551 PST the same day. During this time, wind gusts of 70 mph or greater were measured each hour for approximately 7 hours, with a peak gust of 75 mph between 0751 and 0851 PST. Sustained winds were 50 mph or greater during many of these hours as well.
column38: This event was an upper-level low that followed an inside slider trajectory, passing just north of the region and providing gusty north-northeast winds on the 22nd and 23rd, but little in the way of precipitation. The hardest hit areas were the Cajon Pass (I-15 through the San Bernardino Mountains) and areas below that in the Inland Empire which recorded wind gusts in the 45 to 65 mph range, with at least one gust in the 70s. Strong winds blew over several semi trucks, one causing injuries to the driver. Several high wind gusts were also reported nearby. As the winds turned more northeast-east on the 23rd into the 24th, San Diego County was affected as well, though most winds did not exceed high wind criteria. Instead the mountains in that area experienced wind gusts in the 40 to 55 mph range.

column37: High winds began at the Fremont Canyon RAWS between 0651 and 0751 PST on the 23rd and ended between 0751 and 0851 PST. During that time, a peak gust of 63 mph was measured between 0751 and 0851 PST. |The nearby Santiago Peak mesonet station recorded a peak gust of 60 mph earlier that morning around 0400 PST.
column38: This event was an upper-level low that followed an inside slider trajectory, passing just north of the region and providing gusty north-northeast winds on the 22nd and 23rd, but little in the way of precipitation. The hardest hit areas were the Cajon Pass (I-15 through the San Bernardino Mountains) and areas below that in the Inland Empire which recorded wind gusts in the 45 to 65 mph range, with at least one gust in the 70s. Strong winds blew over several semi trucks, one causing injuries to the driver. Several high wind gusts were also reported nearby. As the winds turned more northeast-east on the 23rd into the 24th, San Diego County was affected as well, though most winds did not exceed high wind criteria. Instead the mountains in that area experienced wind gusts in the 40 to 55 mph range.

column37: The San Diego Lindbergh Field ASOS reported visibility of one-eighth of a mile from 0351 to 0528 PST on the morning of the 30th and again on the morning of the 31st from 0201 to 0250 PST. |Zero visibility was reported at nearby Coronado Cays near Chula Vista.
column38: A shallow marine layer resulted in areas of dense fog along the coastal areas in Orange County, the San Diego coastal mesas and the Western San Diego County valleys. Visibility was a below a quarter mile in many locations for several hours in the overnight and early morning periods from the 29th through the 31st. Operations at John Wayne and San Diego International Airports were impacted for several hours both nights.

column37: Lindbergh Field ASOS reported 1/8 mile visibility from 0322 to 0550 PST, from 0624 to 0850 PST and again from 2025 to 2229 PST on the 1st. The following day, Carlsbad Palomar Airport ASOS reported less than 1/4 mile visibility from 2353 PST on the 1st to 0052 PST on the 2nd. During these mornings, Mission Beach lifeguards reported visibilities of 1/8 mile or less.
column38: A very shallow marine layer created dense fog conditions along the Orange and San Deigo County coasts during the nights and early mornings of the 1st and 2nd. Several coastal airports and beaches reported less than 1/4 mile visibility for hours at a time, some even dropping below 1/8 mile. No aircraft accidents were reported during these times.

column37: High winds began at the Fremont Canyon RAWS between 1900 and 2000 PST on the 7th and ended between 1100 and 1200 PST on the 8th. Several gusts over 60 mph were recorded during this time, with a peak gust of 82 mph between 0351 and 0451 PST on the 8th. |High winds began at the Santiago Peak mesonet station between 0030 and 0130 PST and ended between 0745 and 0945 PST on the 8th. During this time, a peak gust of 66 mph was recorded between 0119 and 0300 PST.
column38: An upper-level shortwave trough developed over the Great Basin and moved south and east through Arizona, creating a significant offshore flow event for Southern California from the evening of the 7th through the 8th. Winds of 15 to 25 mph with gusts as high as 82 mph blew through the Inland Empire, Santa Ana Mountains and nearby canyons and passes. For this event, most stations in the San Diego County valleys remained below 50 mph with no damage reported.

column37: High winds occurred much of the early afternoon in the Borrego area of San Diego County, with plenty of blowing dust. At approximately 1415 PST, the spotter measured a wind gust of 74 mph on his home weather station.
column38: A powerful, elongated jet brought back to back storm systems (one on the 21st and one on the 23rd) through southern California with very strong west-northwest winds in all of the mountain and desert areas. Probably the most damage occurred in the Coachella Valley, where a prominent professional golf tournament was being held. Several stations in the upper deserts reported wind gusts over 75 mph, some reaching nearly 100 mph. The Coachella Valley experienced gusts over 60 mph, including the Palm Springs Airport, which rarely sees winds that strong. Multiple reports of power lines and poles down, as well as carports and signs knocked over. Many locations in the Palm Springs area experienced zero visibility in blowing dust as well, closing several major roadways. The second system on the 23rd, was nowhere near as damaging, but still recorded some impressive winds. |All in all, over 400 trees were reported damaged or down in the Palm Springs area and around $600,000 in damage for Riverside County during the event.

column37: High winds occurred at the Harrison Park SDGE weather station between 1400 and 1600 PST on the 23rd. During that time two gusts of 58 mph were recorded, as well as the peak gust of 59 mph measured between 1310 and 1320 PST.
column38: A powerful, elongated jet brought back to back storm systems (one on the 21st and one on the 23rd) through southern California with very strong west-northwest winds in all of the mountain and desert areas. Probably the most damage occurred in the Coachella Valley, where a prominent professional golf tournament was being held. Several stations in the upper deserts reported wind gusts over 75 mph, some reaching nearly 100 mph. The Coachella Valley experienced gusts over 60 mph, including the Palm Springs Airport, which rarely sees winds that strong. column37: High winds began at the Fremont Canyon RAWS on the 27th 0651 and 0751 PST and ended between 1351 and 1451 PST. During that time, several gusts over 58 mph were recorded, including a peak gust of 61 mph measured twice (once at the beginning and once at the end) between the high wind interval. |High winds began again between 1751 and 1851 PST on the 27th and ended between 0751 and 0851 PST on the 28th. During that period, wind gusts were consistently above 60 mph and sustained winds were above 40 mph for the majority of the hours. A peak gust of 82 mph was measured between 0351 and 0451 PST on the 28th.
column38: Behind the powerful jet that brought back to back storms through southern California, upper level high pressure built back in over the eastern Pacific, resulting in strong northerly (offshore) flow over the region on the mornings of the 27th and 28th. The typical canyon/pass areas and Inland Empire received the strongest winds, both sustained and gusts. Many stations reported sustained winds over 40 mph along with several gusts over 60 mph. Despite the strong gusts and sustained winds, only a few damage reports came in regarding power poles and containers blown off of a semi truck.

column37: Wind gusts over 50 mph were recorded at the Lucky Five Ranch mesonet station between 0840 and 1120 PST on the 28th. During that time, a peak gust of 59 mph was measured between 0920 and 0930 PST.
column38: Behind the powerful jet that brought back to back storms through southern California, upper level high pressure built back in over the eastern Pacific, resulting in strong northerly (offshore) flow over the region on the mornings of the 27th and 28th. The typical canyon/pass areas and Inland Empire received the strongest winds, both sustained and gusts. Many stations reported sustained winds over 40 mph along with several gusts over 60 mph. Despite the strong gusts and sustained winds, only a few damage reports came in regarding power poles and containers blown off of a semi truck.

column37: High winds began at the Fremont Canyon RAWS between 0651 and 0751 PST and ended between 1251 and 1351 PST on the 16th. During this time, winds consistently gusted above 60 mph and often above 65 mph. Two peak gust of 73 mph was recorded between 1851 and 2051 PST.
column38: An amplified ridge over the eastern Pacific allowed a few upper-level short wave troughs to move over the region from the 11th through the 13th, resulting in strong, gusty winds and widespread light rain. These passing troughs culminated in a closed upper-level low over San Diego the 14th through the 16th. This cold, closed low dropped south and inland bringing widespread rain and heavy mountain snow to the CWA. |On the 14th, San Diego County received the highest rain amounts due to instability showers in the northwest flow behind the shortwave trough axis. Amounts were generally between 0.15 and 0.50 inches of rain, with around three-quarters of an inch on the coastal mountain slopes. Areas above 3500 feet received 2 to 4 inches of snow, with up to 5 inches at 5000 feet. The Riverside County Mountains received 1 to 2 inches of snow above 5000 feet, while the San Bernardino County Mountains fared somewhat better with a trace to 3 inches above 4000 feet and up to 6 inches around 7000 feet. |The system stalled out over San Diego for the 15th and 16th. The snow level dropped to around 2800 feet that day. The San Bernardino County Mountains came in with a trace up to 5 inches in the range from 3000 to 6000 feet and generally 6 to 8 inches above 7000 feet, with locally higher amounts of 12 to 14 inches in places such as Idyllwild and Big Bear City. The Riverside County Mountains had higher amounts with 10 to 14 inches above 5000 feet and up to 20 inches around 8000 feet.The San Diego County Mountains received 3 to 6 inches above 3500 feet, including 4 inches of snow in Julian which closed schools in that city on the 13th and 15th. Chain control was required in most mountain locations across the area above 3500 feet. California Highway Patrol even closed Interstate 8 near Pine Valley due to the snow and icy conditions. Rainfall was generally moderate and locally heavy ranging from 0.2 to 0.5 inches in the coast and valley locations, with locally heavier amounts up to 0.8 inches on the mountain slopes. Isolated thunderstorms with accumulating small hail and even a few funnel clouds also occurred in the cold, unstable air behind the front during the morning and early afternoon of the 15th.

column37: San Diego lifeguards at Mission Bay reported visibility of one-eighth of a mile around 0930 PST on the 23rd. Solana Beach lifeguards reported visibility of one-eighth of a mile at Fletcher Cove around 1100 PST on the 23rd. Brown Field ASOS reported visibility less than one-quarter of a mile from 0453-0553 PST on the 24th. Montgomery Field ASOS reported less than one-quarter of a mile visibility at 0653 PST and one-sixteenth of a mile visibility at 0753 PST on the 24th.
column38: A shallow marine layer resulted in dense fog during the nights and early mornings in the San Diego and Orange County coastal basins, as well as the Inland Empire, from the 23rd to the 26th. Numerous lifeguard and ASOS reports confirmed visibility less than one-quarter of a mile and even less than one-eighth of a mile.

column37: Heavy rain caused mud to cover Highway 78, 2 miles east of Scissors Crossing.
column38: A deep, cold trough, associated with its parent upper-level low in the Pacific Northwest, swung through southern California on the 27th, providing the CWA with widespread moderate to locally heavy rainfall and heavy mountain snow. The dynamics were also such that thunderstorms, some with up to pea-sized hail, were also observed. The trajectory of this storm system brought the brunt of the storm through San Diego county providing areas below the snow level and west of the mountains with one-third of an inch to slightly over one inch of rain. Some minor flooding was observed in San Diego County. Orange County and the Inland Empire received less rain, coming in with amounts up to three-quarters of an inch. The snow level was very low with this cold storm, dropping to between 2000 and 2500 feet late in the day. From this level to around 3000 feet had a trace to 3 inches, 3 to 10 inches up to around 7000 feet and up to 14 inches above 7000 feet. Several vehicles slid off the roads in the San Diego County Mountains as well, though no serious injuries were reported. On the lower end of elevation, snow fell as low as 1800 feet in Ramona, however the inch of snow melted later that night. Strong, gusty winds also accompanied this system, most notably in the San Diego County Mountains and the Coachella Valley. San Diego Gas and Electric reported major impacts with this system, including rime ice accumulations on power lines and structures up to a few inches thick.

column37: A mesonet station 5 miles ESE of Cuyamaca Peak measured a wind gust of 64 mph around 2250 PST on the 27th and a gust of 58 mph around 0330 PST on the 28th.|Another mesonet station 5 miles SW of Dulzura measured a wind gust of 60 mph around 2314 PST on the 27th.

column37: High winds began at the Fremont Canyon RAWS between 0651 and 0751 PST on the 2nd and ended between 1051 and 1151 PST. During that time, sustained winds over 40 mph were recorded for several hours as well as a peak gust of 65 mph between 0751 and 0851 PST.
column38: High pressure built off the west coast behind a departing upper-level low pressure system, leading to strong and gusty north to northeast winds in the mountains, Inland Empire and deserts from the 1st through the 3rd. Winds commonly gusted over 60 mph in these areas. The winds blew dust around and caused damage in the Inland Empire and Lucerne Valley. Winds stayed below warning criteria in the San Diego mountains and desert, but many gusts in the low 50s were still reported.

column37: The Borrego State Park District office closed at 1530 PST due to flying debris. Wind had ripped apart a metal awning and a metal parking structure. Winds in Borrego Springs at 1545 PST were sustained at 41 mph and gusting to 47 mph. Visibility was less than 100 yards at times in blowing dust. ||A mobile home residence in Ocotillo Wells was blown over by winds around 1730 PST. NO injuries reported. At 1744 PST, winds were sustained 21 mph, gusting to 45 mph. At 1808 PST, winds were sustained  at 29 mph, gusting to 62 mph. Ocotillo Wells State Park lost many of its camping ramadas due to the wind. In Palm Canyon Campground at Anza Borrego, an electric golf cart was picked up by the wind and hurled into a visitors motor home.||At 2000 PST, Borrego Springs reported a wind gust of 63 mph. At 2045 PST, winds were sustained at 40 mph, gusting to 59 mph.
column38: A closed upper-level low pressure system took an inside slider trajectory, dragging a strong cold front through southern California. This resulted in very strong winds in the mountains and deserts as the front moved through and only light precipitation over and west of the mountains. Behind the front, as the low departed off to the east, the winds turned north to northeast affecting the mountain passes, Inland Empire and Santa Ana mountains. Many stations reported gusts over 60 mph, several over 70 mph and even a few above 80 mph. This resulted in areas of blowing dust, flying debris and damage to a few mobile homes.

column37: High wind began at the Harrison Park mesonet station between 0530 and 0600 PST and ended between 1045 and 1100 PST on the 17th. During that time, a peak gust of 67 mph was measured between 0940 and 0950 PST. There were also several other gusts above 60 mph measured there that day.
column38: A strong, cold upper-level low developed over the north Pacific, with a deep trough and strong, embedded jet extending all the way down to southern California. The main area of precipitation passed through the area the 17th through the 19th, providing widespread moderate to heavy precipitation over and west of the mountains. Areas west of the mountains generally received between one-half of an inch, and one inch of rain, through San Diego County came in somewhat higher, with some amounts near 2 inches along the coastal slopes. According to the Lytle Creek HADS gauge, approximately 3 inches of rain fell in the Lytle Creek drainage (mostly over a three-hour period), causing a 2 to 3 foot rise in the creek at a point where the bed was 25 feet wide. This rise in flow did not leave the creek banks. There were also several other instances of rocks and mud in roadways, but no major flooding occurrences. The San Bernardino County Mountains were the big snow winners with Arrowbear coming in at 28 inches, Big Bear with 12 inches and Wrightwood with 7 to 13 inches. The San Diego County Mountains were not far behind with Cuyamaca receiving 15+ inches, Julian with 12 inches, and Palomar Mountain with 10 inches. Snow drifts in the San Bernardino and San Diego Mountains were upwards of 2 to 3 feet in some areas. Most areas between 3000 and 7000 feet received between 4 and 10 inches, which when melted and combined with rain received up to 3 to 4 inches of liquid equivalent. One location, near the Lake Arrowhead COOP station reported around 5 inches of water equivalent. The snow level was particularly low with this event, bringing as much as 3 inches of snow down to around 2500 feet. Graupel was observed in Temecula, accumulating to around an inch at 1200 feet. The upper deserts received moderate amounts of rain ranging from less than one-quarter inch to over three-quarters of an inch at Phelan. Some snow fell near the desert mountain slopes as well, with Hesperia at around 1 inch. The lower deserts fared quite well, with one-tenth to one-quarter of an inch in the Coachella Valley and one-quarter to slightly over one inch in the San Diego County deserts.|Strong, gusty winds also accompanied this system. Numerous gusts over 60 mph resulted in power outages, blowing dust and traffic signs blown down.

column37: Heavy rain caused a rock slide across Sunrise Highway (S1) near mile marker 18.

The Banner fire started around 1315 PST on the 24th, near the intersection of Highway 78 and S-2, east of Julian near Shelter Valley. No structures or homes were damaged or destroyed, but at one point, 50 residences and one commercial building were threatened. Three firefighters were also injured during the incident, although details of those injuries are unknown. The fire burned a total of 5,321 acres before being fully contained on the 28th.

The Old fire started around 1300 PST on the 17th, northeast of Campo off of Old Highway 80. Approximately 200 structures were threatened and evacuated. One residence and one RV were destroyed in the blaze. Eastbound Highway 94 was closed at Church Road and Old Highway 80 was closed at Crestwood and Live Oak Springs. The fire burned a total of 995 acres before being fully contained on the 19th. There were 2 reported fire fighter injuries.

The Chihuahua fire was started by lightning around 1213 PST on the 9th, along Chihuahua Valley Road near Sunshine Summit, northwest of Warner Springs. There were 250 residences and 100 other structures threatened by the fire, leading to mandatory evacuations of the residences and a Boy Scout camp along Chihuahua Valley Road. A hard closure was in place on Chihuahua Valley Road at Highway 79. No structures were destroyed, but two firefighters received unknown injuries. The fire burned a total of 2007 acres before being fully contained around 1730 PST on the 12th.

column37: The SDGE East Warners sensor recorded a 58 mph gust during a thunderstorm. A spotter also reported marble to penny sized hail (0.75 inch) 2 to 3 miles east of the San Felipe Road turnoff of SR 79.
column38: These days were a continuation of the deep monsoonal flow that persisted over the area through much of the month. Thunderstorms developed each afternoon over the mountains, deserts and northern inland valleys, and quickly diminished by sunset with areas of rural, urban and flash flooding. Flooding activity on the 11th was focused around Big Bear and Victorville in San Bernardino County, as well as Campo in San Diego County. Thunderstorm activity also developed along the Elsinore Convergence Zone in eastern Riverside County. Thunderstorms in this area became severe and produced a couple damaging microbursts along with the small hail and heavy rain. Similar storms in the Elsinore area on the 12th produced a landspout and another damaging microburst. Significant flooding was also observed in the Forest Falls area on that day. Mostly minor urban flooding was observed in the upper deserts and Forest Falls again on the 13th.

The Vallecito Lightning Complex was started by lightning around 1900 PST on the 12th. This complex was composed of 3 larger fires greater than 500 acres and 3 smaller fires of 5 acres or less. The Vallecito Fire burned 519 acres just southeast of Julian. The Stewart Fire burned 10,632 acres near Scissors Crossing northeast of Julian. The Wilson Fire burned 11,669 acres, also near Scissors Crossing northeast of Julian. The Cooper, Wynola and Shoots Fires, together, burned around 7 acres. Evacuations were in place for these areas. No structures were destroyed, but 4 firefighters received unknown injuries. All fires were reported 100% contained on the 19th around 0530 PST after burning a grand total of 22,828 acres in eastern San Diego County.

column37: Law Enforcement reported an oak tree blown down across Lilac Rd near the intersection of San Luis Rey Drive. A newspaper article reported additional trees blown down across Lilac Road near the intersection of Couser Canyon Road. ||A NWS employee reported three large pine trees downed by wind along Highway 76 south of Palomar Mountain. The largest of the uprooted pine trees was 18 to 20 inches in diameter, and healthy. A weather spotter estimated a 40 MPH wind gust in the area. The SDGE weather station at Cuca Ranch reported a wind gust of 42 MPH just before 1630 PST.
column38: Monsoonal moisture in easterly flow aloft brought showers and thunderstorms to the mountains and deserts each afternoon and evening. The activity on the 9th was mainly in the upper deserts, San Bernardino Mountains and the Inland Empire near Lake Elsinore. Flooding was reported along Highway 74 in Lake Elsinore with 3 to 5 inches of water covering the roadway, along with several downed trees, and a land spout in the nearby city of Perris. Outflow boundaries from storms created strong winds which picked up dust and lowered visibility in the Coachella Valley and near Borrego Springs. Visibility was also lowered to near zero at times with wind gusts around 60 MPH reported in the areas. Storms were more widespread on the 10th as a trough of low pressure drifted north from Mexico. Thunderstorms occurred over most mountain and desert locations, as well as the Inland Empire. Flash flooding was reported in Forest Falls and along Highway 76 in northern San Diego County. Highway 76 was closed for about an hour in the afternoon due to 12 to 18 inches of mud and debris in the road.

column37: The SDGE station at Borrego Springs measured sustained winds of 34 mph with gusts to 60 mph at 1930 PST. Law enforcement reported visibility of less than one-sixteenth of a mile (300 feet) in blowing dust during that time.

Highway 76 was closed for about an hour in the afternoon due to 12 to 18 inches of mud and debris in the road.

column37: The mesonet station of Eastern Tanks at La Jolla Amago recorded 1.46 inches of rain between 1311 and 1400 PST.|The mesonet station at the La Jolla Indian Reservation recorded 1.54 inches of rain between 1317 and 1405 PST.

The Shockey fire started around 1114 PST on the 23rd, near the intersection of the Shockey Truck Trail and Highway 94, east of Campo in San Diego County. As the fire burned rapidly, approximately 25 structures were threatened. Two residences were damaged, 11 other residences destroyed along with 14 outbuildings and 11 vehicles. Mandatory evacuations were in place for approximately 125 residents in the communities of Tierra del Sol, Boulevard and Jewell Valley. Shelters were opened at Mountain Empire High School (animal sheltering as well) and the Campo Tribal Shelter. Three child care facilities voluntarily evacuated as well. Highway 94 was closed from the Shockey Truck Trail east to Jewell Valley and the Mexican border. Three firefighters received unknown injuries. A 69-year old male was found dead in his home due to burn injuries and smoke inhalation. The fire burned a total of 2556 acres before being fully contained around 1900 PST on the 26th. The fire started in an area where target shooting occurs, but the exact cause of the fire is still unknown.

column37: The Sill Hill SDGE site, just northwest of Cuyamaca Peak, reported sustained winds of 40 to 46 mph with frequent gusts of 58 mph or greater between 0050 and 0420 PST. The peak gust of 66 mph occurred around 0320 PST.
column38: Surface high pressure over the Great Basin brought strong and gusty northeast winds through and below the passes and canyons. The San Diego mountain areas recorded several gusts over 45 mph. The same occurred below the Banning Pass in the Inland Empire and the canyons in and below the Santa Ana Mountains. Three stations, however did reach high wind criteria. No damage was reported with these gusts.

column37: High winds began at the Mt. Laguna North mesonet station between 0100 and 0200 PST on the 8th and ended between 0600 and 0700 PST the same day. During this time, winds were sustained 40-60 mph with several gusts over 65 mph. The peak gust of 70 mph was recorded between 0400 and 0500 PST. ||The Volcan Mountain SDGE mesonet station reported sustained winds above 40 mph between 0430 and 0600 PST. A peak gust of 60 mph was recorded between 0500 and 0510 PST.
column38: A cold low pressure system from the Gulf of Alaska moved through California, bringing light to moderate precipitation. A few locations in the San Diego County and San Bernardino County Mountains received between 1 and 2 inches of rain. One of these locations experienced a debris flow along State Route 18, in the upper Waterman Canyon just south of Crestline, where boulders the size of beer kegs washed across both lanes of the highway. Strong and gusty west to northwest winds accompanied this system, with several mountain and desert slope stations reporting sustained winds over 45 mph and gusts to 80 mph.

column37: High winds began at the Mt. Laguna North mesonet station between 0200 and 0300 PST on the 9th and ended between 1200 and 1300 PST the same day. During this time, winds were sustained 55-68 mph with gusts over 67-76 mph. The peak gust of 76 mph was recorded between 0700 and 0800 PST.||High winds began at the Volcan Mountain mesonet station between 0130 and 0140 PST on the 9th and ended between 1420 and 1430 PST the same day. During this time, winds were sustained over 40 mph with frequent gusts 57-70 mph. The peak gust of 70 mph was recorded between 0720 and 0730 PST.||High winds began at the Harrison Park mesonet station between 0320 and 0330 PST on the 9th and ended between 0500 and 1730 PST the same day. During this time, winds were sustained 41-46 mph. The peak gust of 60 mph was recorded twice between 0440 and 0500 PST.

A few locations in the San Diego County and San Bernardino County Mountains received between 1 and 2 inches of rain. One of these locations experienced a debris flow along State Route 18, in the upper Waterman Canyon just south of Crestline, where boulders the size of beer kegs washed across both lanes of the highway. Strong and gusty west to northwest winds accompanied this system, with several mountain and desert slope stations reporting sustained winds over 45 mph and gusts to 80 mph.

column37: Brown Field ASOS reported one-quarter mile visibility from 1253 to 0818 PST. Montgomery Field ASOS reported one-quarter mile visibility from 0253 to 0853 PST.
column38: Clear skies, high humidity just inland from the coast, along with the radiational cooling allowed dense fog to form near the coast during the nights and early mornings of the 23rd and 25th. Drainage flow kept the fog within about 10 miles of the coast, with the exception of the inland, low area of Ramona. Multiple airports reported visibilities less than 1/4 mile for several hours on each of those mornings. The fog created some airport delays as well as security problems for the Border Patrol along the Mexican Border and along the coast up to San Clemente.

column37: Carlsbad-Palomar Airport ASOS reported visibility of one-quarter mile or less from 2141 PST on the 24th to 1000 PST on the 25th. Brown Field ASOS reported visibility of one-quarter mile or less from 2053 PST on the 24th to 0921 PST on the 25th, except between 0123 and 0153 when the visibility briefly improved. Miramar Airport ASOS reported visibility of one-quarter mile or less from 2355 PST on the 24th to 0855 PST on the 25th, down to one-sixteenth of a mile between 0055 and 0736 PST on the 25th. Montgomery Field ASOS reported visibility of one-quarter mile or less from 1253 to 0838 PST on the 25th. A spotter in Allied Gardens reported visibility less than one-quarter mile around 0212 PST.

column37: High winds began at the Volcan Mountain SDGE mesonet between 0850 and 0900 PST on the 24th and ended between 1320 and 1330 PST the same day. During this time winds mostly gusted over 60 mph, with a peak gust of 70 mph between 1110 and 1120 PST.
column38: A weak trough moved through southern California late on the 23rd into the morning of the 24th, providing another round of light to moderate precipitation, and strong winds in the mountains and desert slopes. Many locations gusted over 50 mph during the morning and early afternoon of the 24th. Another, deeper, trough dug south through the region and on the 26th into the morning of the 27th, bringing more strong, gusty winds to the mountains and desert slopes.

column37: High winds began at the Sill Hill mesonet station around 1830 PST on the 1st and lasted, off and on, until 0800 on the 2nd. During this time, several gusts over 60 mph were recorded, including the peak gust of 64 mph measured between 0720 and 0730 PST on the 2nd.
column38: A compact upper-level low dropped south along the California coast, before moving inland over northern Baja, Mexico on the 1st and 2nd. Because of the limited moisture and inland trajectory, no precipitation was observed. However, there were strong, gusty west winds in the mountains and deserts those days.

column37: High winds began at the Volcan Mountain SDGE mesonet between 0800 and 0810 PST on the 10th and ended between 1550 and 1600 PST the same day. During this time, winds gusted above 60 mph almost the entire time. This included a few gusts above 70 mph and the peak gust of 73 mph, which was measured between 1300 and 1310 PST. |High winds also occurred at the Harrison Park mesonet, between 1030 and 1430 PST on the 10th. During this time, sustained winds were around 45 mph with gusts over 60 mph. This included the peak gust of 63 mph, which was measured between 1340 and 1350 PST.
column38: A cold trough of low pressure dropped down the West Coast, before closing off over southern California. This system brought light to locally moderate showers to most areas, except the Coachella Valley, on the afternoon and evening of the 6th. Light showers lingered into the morning of the 7th near the mountains. Rainfall totals for the coast and valleys were mostly light, generally ranging from one-tenth to one-third of an inch, with three-quarters of an inch to an inch for the lower mountains and foothills. The lower deserts generally received less than one-tenth of an inch, with the exception of Borrego Springs with 0.16 inches of rain. The snow level fell to between 3500 and 4000 feet, with 1 to 3 inches of snow below 6000 feet, and up to 6 inches above 6000 feet.On the 10th, a very cold trough of low pressure from the northwest moved through southern California, bringing significant cooling, low snow levels, gusty west winds and light to locally moderate precipitation along and west of the mountains. The snow level dropped to around 2500 feet, with accumulating snow of around one-half inch down to around 3000 feet in locations such as Hesperia and the Cajon Pass in San Bernardino County, and Julian in San Diego County. Up to 5 inches of snow fell above 4000 feet. Chains were required in most mountain areas as well. Gusty winds also accompanied the storm on the 10th, even resulting in some blowing dust in the Coachella Valley. Strong winds across the coastal waters, combined with a large swell and astronomical high tides, resulted in minor coastal flooding during the morning of the 11th in La Jolla, Imperial Beach and Newport Beach. Most flooding was limited to a few beach parking lots and some nearby surface streets.

column37: High winds began at the Fremont Canyon RAWS between 0251 and 0351 PST on the 14th and ended between 0551 and 0651 PST the same morning. During this time, sustained winds were 45 to 48 mph with gusts over 60 mph, including the peak gust of 71 mph measured between 0351 and 0451 PST.
column38: On the 14th, the trough slowly began shifting eastward, allowing dry and warmer offshore flow to develop and providing gusty, northerly high winds through the passes and canyons, filtering down into the Inland Empire, causing some damage in the form of downed power lines and road signs. There were several stations reporting sustained winds of 40 mph or greater and gusts over 60 mph.

column37: There were two periods of high winds at the Sill Hill SDGE mesonet station. The first was between 2050 and 2110 PST on the 15th, with a peak gust of 62 mph. The second was  between 1240 and 0110 PST pm the 16th, with a peak gust of 66 mph around 0100 PST.|The Lucky Five mesonet station gusted between 40 and 50 mph for several hours that night, but hit a peak gust of 58 mph between 0140 and 0150 PST on the 16th.
column38: On the 14th, the trough slowly began shifting eastward, allowing dry and warmer offshore flow to develop and providing gusty, northerly high winds through the passes and canyons, filtering down into the Inland Empire, causing some damage in the form of downed power lines and road signs. There were several stations reporting sustained winds of 40 mph or greater and gusts over 60 mph.

column37: Dense fog was intermittent at Montgomery Field between 0500 and 1600 PST on the 26th with visibilities of one-quarter mile or less. The lowest visibility was one-eighth of a mile around 1445 PST. Visibility at Lindbergh Field was one-quarter mile at 0725 PST that morning. The low ceilings and visibility resulted in numerous flight delays.
column38: A coastal marine fog (warm air over cold water) resulted in areas of dense fog in the coastal San Diego area during the early morning of the 26th. The ceilings and low visibility in fog resulted in airport delays at Lindbergh Field.

column37: High winds began at the Mt. Laguna North mesonet station between 2300 PST on the 7th and 0000 PST on the 8th and ended between 0100 and 0200 PST on the 8th. During this time, winds gusted to 68 mph between 2303 and 0102 PST on the 8th.|High sustained winds of 40 to 43 mph occurred at the Volcan Mountain mesonet station between 2310 and 0100 PST on the 7th-8th. A peak gust of 59 was measured between 2330 and 2340 PST.
column38: A very cold trough of low pressure from the northwest moved through southern California on the 7th through the 10th, bringing significant cooling, low snow levels, gusty west winds and light to locally moderate precipitation along and west of the mountains. A few embedded thunderstorms were also observed on the 8th, producing periods of pea-sized hail and graupel. Hail accumulation was blamed for multiple accidents, closing portion of Interstate 15 near El Cajon. Rainfall totals for the coast and valleys were mostly light, generally ranging from one-tenth to one-third of an inch, with three-quarters of an inch to an inch for the lower mountains and foothills. The lower deserts generally received less than one-tenth of an inch, with the exception of Borrego Springs with 0.16 inches of rain. The snow level dropped to 1500-2000 feet, with accumulating snow of 1-3 inches down to around 2600 feet in locations such as Beaumont and Yucaipa in the Inland Empire and Banning Pass. Significant snow fell above 5000 feet, with many locations receiving 6-12 inches. Some higher locations in the San Bernardino County mountains, such as Big Bear and Onyx Summit received up to 22 inches. During this storm, a major manhunt was underway for an ex-LAPD officer who was on the run after a killing spree. All major national news outlets were covering the search. A weak trough moved southward, early on the 10th, and interacted with residual low level moisture to produce a few light showers, mainly in the mountains and inland valleys of San Diego County. These showers only amounted to a tenth of an inch or less.

column37: Strong winds, along with pea-sized hail damaged a biomedical firm's roof in Sorrento Valley. A 20 by 30 foot section of skylight paneling was torn off from the company's rooftop.
column38: A very cold trough of low pressure from the northwest moved through southern California on the 7th through the 10th, bringing significant cooling, low snow levels, gusty west winds and light to locally moderate precipitation along and west of the mountains. A few embedded thunderstorms were also observed on the 8th, producing periods of pea-sized hail and graupel. Hail accumulation was blamed for multiple accidents, closing portion of Interstate 15 near El Cajon. Rainfall totals for the coast and valleys were mostly light, generally ranging from one-tenth to one-third of an inch, with three-quarters of an inch to an inch for the lower mountains and foothills. The lower deserts generally received less than one-tenth of an inch, with the exception of Borrego Springs with 0.16 inches of rain. The snow level dropped to 1500-2000 feet, with accumulating snow of 1-3 inches down to around 2600 feet in locations such as Beaumont and Yucaipa in the Inland Empire and Banning Pass. Significant snow fell above 5000 feet, with many locations receiving 6-12 inches. Some higher locations in the San Bernardino County mountains, such as Big Bear and Onyx Summit received up to 22 inches. During this storm, a major manhunt was underway for an ex-LAPD officer who was on the run after a killing spree. All major national news outlets were covering the search. A weak trough moved southward, early on the 10th, and interacted with residual low level moisture to produce a few light showers, mainly in the mountains and inland valleys of San Diego County. These showers only amounted to a tenth of an inch or less.

The high quickly broke down on March 2nd, then an approaching upper level low pressure trough created gusty west winds on March 3rd.

column37: In Oceanside, lots of small branches and pots were knocked over and a 12 foot shed was tossed approximately 100 feet, based on where it was located originally and the scrape marks where it landed on the street. At least two vehicles were damaged, one with a side mirror damaged by the shed and another had a large tree limb approximately 4 to 6 inches in diameter that broke the window. At least six screens were knocked off on the windows of the homes. And very unique damage done by pinecones from large trees just to the west which  left large scrape marks on the side of stucco. Based on the damage, winds are estimated to be 45 to 50 mph in the localized three or four block area.|Downed trees were blocking the roadway on Via de Santa Fe and large palm tree branches were in the number 4 lane of southbound Interstate 5 at Harbor Drive according to California Highway Patrol.
column38: A deep trough of low pressure from the northwest moved through southern California, bringing cooling, gusty west winds and moderate precipitation along and west of the mountains, as well as in the upper desert. Rainfall totals for the coast and valleys were significant, especially in San Diego County, where the center of the upper low passed nearly overhead. The main precipitation area, early on the morning of the 8th, also contained embedded thunderstorms with local, damaging winds and pea-sized hail (accumulating in some places). Flooding was limited to minor urban ponding and runoff on sidewalks and roadways. The snow level dropped to around 2900 feet, with 1 to 4 inches of snow down to between 3500 and 4000 feet. Most locations above 5000 feet received 7 to 14 inches of snow, with local amounts up to 16 inches in the Riverside County mountains near Idyllwild.

column37: High winds began at the Borrego Springs around 0700 PST on the 8th and ended around 1100 PST that morning. During this time, there were periods of high winds and lull periods. A peak gust of 73 mph was measured around 0840 PST. A spotter reported sustained winds of 53 mph with a gust to 83 mph around 1000 PST. This gust was blamed for downing the major power line running through the town. Several branches were also downed, with at least one road blocked. Another spotter reported a downed power pole and trees, as well as shingles blown off a roof, damaging a car. Visibility reported 2 miles in blowing dust for a time. Blowing sand pitted several vehicle windshields in the area as well, causing some windows to shatter. Significant damage was reported at the Anza-Borrego State Park, with Ranger HQ parking structures damaged, along with three Mongolian ger tents used by campers and 800 square feet of roof from the Stout Paleontology Laboratory.
column38: A deep trough of low pressure from the northwest moved through southern California, bringing minor cooling, gusty, light to moderate precipitation along and west of the mountains and damaging west winds to the mountains and deserts. West winds were sustained 30-50 mph with gusts up to 80-90 mph. Damage to trees and structures, as well as blowing dust and sand, was reported in the Borrego Springs and Palm Springs areas. A big rig was also blown over along Interstate 10 in Palm Springs. Rainfall totals for the southwest and west slopes of the San Bernardino County mountains were also significant for this event. Amounts from one-quarter of an inch up to 1.5 inches were recorded.

column38: A large upper-level low over the Pacific Northwest deepened and swung through the Great Basin the evening of the 14th through the 16th, driving strong and gusty westerly winds across the mountains and deserts. These winds resulted in widespread blowing dust in the Coachella Valley, with visibilities down to one-eights of a mile or less at times and accumulating sand, closing main roadways through the valley. Several mountain stations recorded sustained winds of 35-45 mph and gusts 60 to 80 mph. Following this event a weak upper low off the coast produced elevated thunderstorms in northwest San Diego County, with 60 total strikes and up to 1/2 size hail during the evening of April 24th.

column37: High winds began at the Fremont Canyon RAWS between 0451 and 0551 PST on the 2nd and ended between 0951 and 1051 PST the same day. During this time, winds were sustained 30 to 45 mph with gusts mostly above 60 mph, including the peak gust of 70 mph measured between 0651 and 0751 PST.
column38: Surface high pressure built into the Great Basin, bringing strong and gusty northeast winds through and below passes and canyons during the morning of the 2nd. Winds temporarily decreased that night, before increasing again, somewhat, the morning of the 3rd.

The Chariot Fire started around 1155 PST on July 6, near Chariot Canyon Road at Oriflamme Canyon Road in Vallecito, San Diego County. The location is east of Sunrise Highway and about 9 miles southeast of Julian. The rugged terrain and poor access hindered control efforts. The cause of the fire is still unknown. Laguna, El Prado, Fosters and Horsehaven Campgrounds were evacuated of an unknown number of campers. Twenty campers were evacuated from Shriners Camp to a shelter in Alpine.  Sunrise Highway/County Road 1 was closed from SR-79 to Old Highway 80. The fire threatened 120 residential structures and destroyed 118 structures, of undetermined type, plus 2 commercial buildings. The communication site on Monument Peak, as well as other nearby campgrounds in the Cleveland National Forest were threatened as well. Approximately 7 firefighters sustained unknown injuries. The fire burned 7,055 acres before being fully contained around 1700 PST on July 15.

The Falls Fire started around 0900 PST on the 5th, off of the Ortega Highway near Decker Canyon, in Riverside. The cause of the fire is still unknown. Due to the fire burning on the Trabuco Ranger District, the San Mateo Wilderness, El Cariso Campground, Blue Jay Campground, the Firefighter Memorial Picnic Area and Wildomar OHV area were closed. Road closures included the Ortega Hwy 74 from Lake Elsinore west to San Antonio Parkway. Intermittent road openings were allowed to residents only. Evacuations were ordered for Lakeland Village, Rancho Capistrano and Decker Canyon residents. Evacuation perimeter is between Grand/Ortega and Grand/Corydon. No structures were threatened and no injuries. Minor guardrail damage occurred as a result of a rock fall along the Ortega Highway. The fire burned 1416 acres before being fully contained around 1700 PST on the 9th.

column37: The Barrett RAWS measured a gust of 70 mph between 1350 and 1450 PST from a collapsing nearby thunderstorm. These winds were responsible for one small tree down, as well as branches and debris on Barrett Lake Road.
column38: Isolated to scattered thunderstorms continued over the mountains, deserts, and portions of the Inland Empire, producing flash flooding each afternoon and evening through the 7th, with a brief lull in activity on the 1st. The hot spots on the 3rd were in the San Diego and Riverside County mountains, as well as the Coachella Valley. Storms in the Idyllwild/Pine Cove area produced flash flooding along Highway 243 and hail up to one-half inch. The Palm Springs area experienced flooding due to runoff from storms in the adjacent mountains, closing Araby Drive. Mountain storms also resulted in a flash flood and debris flow that raced down Tahquitz Creek and flowed through the Tahquitz Creek golf resort, closing Cathedral Canyon Drive at the Whitewater Wash. Areas in Riverside County also received accumulating small hail and severe winds from collapsing thunderstorms. Activity on the 4th and 5th favored similar areas, with more flash flooding. Runoff from storms over the Mountain Fire burn area in the San Jacinto Mountains resulted in a flash flood and debris flow 2 feet deep and 20 feet wide across Golf Club Drive in Cathedral City. Heavy rain also caused flooding on Highway 74 at McCall Road in Idyllwild, as well as Interstate 8 between Willows Road and Japatul. On the 6th, mud and water covered Highway S2 near the SR 79 intersection, closing that road due to multiple vehicles stuck in the mud. Pea to dime sized hail and damaging winds also accompanied these storms. Heavy rain caused minor road flooding in the Pine Valley area, with 1 to 2 inches of water flowing over several roadways. Highway 247 at Bessemer Mine Road had a 50-foot wide area of fast-moving water flowing across it, just east of Lucerne Valley. On the 7th, heavy rain near Forest Falls resulted in the normally dry Mill Creek running 2 feet deep and about 50 feet wide, stranding campers on one side of the creek. In San Diego County, there were 5 or 6 spots of water running across Highway 94 between Shockey Truck Trail and Sheridan Road with a maximum water depth of 6 inches. Waves of water up to 8 inches deep, with mud and debris, flowed rapidly over Highway 78 a few miles east of Julian. Highway 78 was impacted again as it dropped down into the desert, with 3 to 8 inches of water, in an area approximately 75 yards wide, flowing across the highway. Golf Club Drive in Cathedral City was closed again due to flooding from the Whitewater Wash.

column38: A large area of surface high pressure built in over the Great Basin, creating approximately 14 millibars of offshore flow from Salt Lake City to the coast of San Diego. This led to temperatures in the low to mid 90s at the coast and strong gusty winds over the mountain ridges and through aligned canyons and passes. Riverside and Orange County were primarily affected on the 4th, then San Diego County on the 5th as the wind shifted more easterly. No wind damage was reported, but the strong winds led to the spread of the De Luz Fire on the Camp Pendleton marine base.

The De Luz fire began on October 5th around 2015 PST near the intersection of Vandergrift Road and Ammunition Road, ONeill Lake on the Camp Pendleton Marine base. There were 100 residences and one commercial structure threatened, but only one outbuilding damaged. The on-base medical facility, as well as the De Luz and O'Neill base housing, was evacuated. The fire burned 2236 acres before being fully contained on October 8th around 1700 PST.

column38: A strong, upper-level low pressure system moved through southern California with gusty westerly winds along the mountain ridges and down the desert slopes. There were three periods of enhanced winds over the mountain ridges and through the aligned passes, with gusts 55-75 mph. Visibility was reduced in the Coachella Valley below the San Gorgonio Pass due to blowing sand and dust. No damage was reported, however. This event was also the first significant precipitation event of the winter season. The rainfall was likely a factor in the 318 accidents that occurred during the event, versus a normal day of 75 accidents.

column37: A Mt. Laguna mesonet station reported wind gusts over 58 mph for the majority of the time between 1930 PST on the 27th and 1900 PST on the 28th, with most gusts well over 60 mph. During this time, a peak gust of 80 mph was recorded between 0135 and 0145 PST on the 28th. The Volcan Mountain mesonet station reported wind gusts over 58 mph for the majority of the time between 0220 PST on the 27th and 1840 PST on the 28th, with most gusts over 60 mph. During this time, a peak gust of 72 mph was recorded between 0440 and 0610 PST on the 28th. The Harrison Park mesonet station reported wind gusts over 58 mph off and on between 0330 and 0720 PST on the 28th. During this time, a peak gust of 61 mph was recorded between 0330 and 0340 PST on the 28th.
column38: A strong, upper-level low moved down the West Coast on the 27th, through the 28th. Strong to severe, pre-frontal, southwest to west winds impacted the northern desert slopes before a powerful 130 knot jet moved around the backside of the low and through southern California, increasing westerly winds in the mountains and lower deserts through the 29th. Several locations reported gusts above 65 mph, with a highest wind gust measured of 85 mph.

column38: As high pressure over the Great Basin weakened, a shallow marine layer was allowed to reform along the coast, leading to dense fog conditions for many coastal locations. Visibility was reduced along portions of Interstates 8 and 15, as well as Highways 52 and 78 in San Diego County. Affected areas in Orange County included sections of Interstates 5 and 405, as well as Highways 73 and 55. Affected airports included Lindbergh Field, Brown Field, Montgomery Field, MCAS Miramar, Carlsbad, Imperial Beach Naval Auxiliary Landing Field and John Wayne Airport; all reported visibility of less than one-quarter of a mile at times overnight into the morning of the 9th.

column38: A cold, upper-level trough of low pressure brought gusty west winds, and scattered showers to the mountains and San Diego County foothills on the 4th. The snow level dropped to around 3000 feet, with a trace to two inches of snow measured from I-8 to Big Bear. Pine Valley schools were closed on the 4th and chain control was enforced around the Big Bear and Pine Cove areas. The strongest winds were fairly well distributed over the area with several gusts above 60 mph.

column38: Surface high pressure peaked at 1045 mb over western Utah(similar in strength to December 9-10 event, which was centered in eastern Nevada) and appeared to be diurnally enhanced due to strong radiational cooling in the Utah desert. This setup resulted in moderate to locally strong Santa Ana winds. The winds developed in the mountains and spread into the inland valleys and coastal areas of Orange county on the 14th, with strengthening winds in San Diego County late in the day. A secondary peak of offshore winds occurred the night of the 14th through midday on the 15th with the strongest winds across the Riverside and San Diego County mountains and foothills. The highest wind gusts were observed in the mountains and foothills of San Diego County.

column38: A strong, upper-level trough brought colder weather along with rain, mountain snow and gusty southwest to west winds to the region. Light rain began during the early morning on the 19th, with most precipitation ending west of the mountains later that night. Showers lingered over the mountains and deserts into the 20th, as moisture wrapped around the surface low pressure system, exiting to the southeast. Coastal and inland valley locations generally received between one-tenth and one-half of an inch of rain, with up to one inch in the coastal foothills of San Diego and San Bernardino Counties. The upper deserts varied widely from no rain in Victorville to one-half inch at the Mojave Dam. Only a few hundredths were reported in the Coachella Valley. Snow levels lowered to 3500 to 4000 feet, bringing 2 to 5 inches of snow to mountain locations above 4500 feet and trace amounts below. Chains were required on Palomar Mountain. This was the last significant precipitation until late January of 2014. Cold air instability also resulted in scattered thunderstorms during the afternoon of the 19th in the valleys and high desert. Very small hail and flooding was reported by a spotter in Anaheim on Miraloma Street between Fee Ana Street and Lakeview, where water flooded over the curbs and in the intersection up to 6 inches deep in places. A spotter in Phelan sent photos of small hail covering their yard. The Coachella Valley saw the highest wind gusts overnight and into the morning of the 19th, with a few in the San Diego County mountains as well.

column37: The Sierra Peak mesonet reported high winds between 0730-1630 PST on the 28th, with a peak gust of 69 mph recorded between 0904-1004 PST. The El Cariso RAWS also reported a peak gust of 70 mph between 1520 and 1620 PST that afternoon.
column38: A weak, upper-level trough moved through California overnight on February 26th, into the morning of the 27th, increasing gusty west winds and bringing a round of light to moderate showers over and west of the mountains. A much stronger, Pacific low pressure system took aim at southern California late on the 27th, bringing periods of heavy rain and high-elevation mountain snow through the 28th (with additional heavy rain through March 1). Most of the upslope rain and convective showers occurred on the 28th. Strong, long-duration upslope flow enhanced rainfall on southwest-facing coastal slopes. The four-day, storm total precipitation amounts were significant. Costal locations ranged from 1 to 3 inches of rain, with the valleys recording up to 4.5 inches toward the coastal slopes. Mountain locations varied widely depending on slope aspect, but most recorded between 3 and 8 inches of rain. The upper deserts recorded between one-tenth and one-half inch, while the lower deserts measured generally less than one-tenth of an inch. The notable exceptions were Palm Springs, Desert Hot Springs in the Coachella Valley and San Felipe in San Diego County, all of which measured between one-half of an inch and one inch. The big rainfall winners were along the southern slopes of the San Bernardino County mountains, with Yucaipa Ridge coming in at 11.11 inches, Lytle Creek with 9.67 inches and Cedar Glen with 9.10 inches. The snow level remained fairly high, around 6000 feet. Most locations saw between 2 and 7 inches of snow, with Big Bear Lake and Onyx Peak recording 9 to 10 inches. The significant rainfall in a relatively short period of time resulted in numerous instances of urban and flash flooding with mud/debris flows, causing numerous road closures and swift water rescues in and around the urban areas of Orange, (Anaheim), San Diego (Escondido and Fashion Valley), and Riverside (Fallbrook to Lake Elsinore) counties. The most significant of these was the mud slides and subsequent road closure of Highway 74 (Ortega Highway) stemming from the Falls Fire burn scar. Many road closures also occurred in the Coachella Valley as a result of heavy rainfall over the headwaters of the Whitewater River, flowing down the valley through the storm channel. Area rivers saw rises of 2 to 5 feet, in some instances within 12 hours. A 10 to 15-foot-tall and eight-foot-wide section of the quarter-mile levee protecting Buckwheat Road from Sheep Creek failed, threatening 8 homes with flood waters. Westerly winds with this system were significant as well, topping numerous large trees and power poles, as well as damage at John Wayne Airport. A report of a 102 mph wind gust came from the Bear Mountain ski resort weather equipment on the 28th. Conditions support this gust, however, no damage was reported. Thunderstorms on the 28th also produced gusty winds, downing several trees and damaging power lines and other structures.

column37: Fox 5 news reported a large tree down in Ocean Beach. San Diego Lindbergh ASOS had a gust of 45 mph at the time. This storm was on the southern end of a squall line (no lightning detected), so possible wet microburst mixing down 50 mph winds at 1 to 2 kft. The same news station reported a 50-year-old tree downed by high winds near downtown San Diego around the same time. Several other trees were downed in the area with this line as well.

The notable exceptions were Palm Springs, Desert Hot Springs in the Coachella Valley and San Felipe in San Diego County, all of which measured between one-half of an inch and one inch. The big rainfall winners were along the southern slopes of the San Bernardino County mountains, with Yucaipa Ridge coming in at 11.11 inches, Lytle Creek with 9.67 inches and Cedar Glen with 9.10 inches. The snow level remained fairly high, around 6000 feet. Most locations saw between 2 and 7 inches of snow, with Big Bear Lake and Onyx Peak recording 9 to 10 inches. The significant rainfall in a relatively short period of time resulted in numerous instances of urban and flash flooding with mud/debris flows, causing numerous road closures and swift water rescues in and around the urban areas of Orange, (Anaheim), San Diego (Escondido and Fashion Valley), and Riverside (Fallbrook to Lake Elsinore) counties. The most significant of these was the mud slides and subsequent road closure of Highway 74 (Ortega Highway) stemming from the Falls Fire burn scar. Many road closures also occurred in the Coachella Valley as a result of heavy rainfall over the headwaters of the Whitewater River, flowing down the valley through the storm channel. Area rivers saw rises of 2 to 5 feet, in some instances within 12 hours. A 10 to 15-foot-tall and eight-foot-wide section of the quarter-mile levee protecting Buckwheat Road from Sheep Creek failed, threatening 8 homes with flood waters. Westerly winds with this system were significant as well, topping numerous large trees and power poles, as well as damage at John Wayne Airport. A report of a 102 mph wind gust came from the Bear Mountain ski resort weather equipment on the 28th. Conditions support this gust, however, no damage was reported. Thunderstorms on the 28th also produced gusty winds, downing several trees and damaging power lines and other structures.
