column38: An upper level high set up over the Four Corners region, allowing moisture to move into Southern California. Showers set up over the coast and valleys on July 22nd, and inland thunderstorms developed in the afternoon. On July 23rd, a severe thunderstorm set up over the Coachella Valley and brought 70 mph winds to Mecca. This resulted in over 8 million dollars in damages to power lines throughout the city. On July 24th, storms prompted flash flood warnings over the Riverside and San Diego County mountains. On July 25th, strong thunderstorms over Julian and Borrego Springs brought gusty winds, small hail and heavy rain.

column37: Spotter reported dense fog on Hwy 78 west between Escondido and Vista. Visibility was between 1/4 and 1/3 of a mile from 0500 to 0700 PST.
column38: Dense fog formed along the coast and in the valleys the morning of August 3rd. In Escondido, visibility was between 1/4 and 1/3 of a mile between 0500 and 0700 PST. In Lake Forest, dense fog was reported on the 241 toll road. Fog lifted and visibility improved after 0700 PST.

column37: Dense fog observed in Escondido on 8/20 at 6:30 am with visibility of 1/8 mile. Fog lifted and visibility improved by 0800 PST.
column38: Dense fog formed along the coast and extended into most valley areas on the morning of August 20th, with visibility as low as 1/8 of a mile at times. Fog lifted and visibility improved after 0800 PST.

column37: An electrical cable was dislodged and was draped across the road. A wind gust of 40 mph was reported about 5 miles to the northwest of this location.
column38: Upper level high pressure centered over the Four Corners ushered in moisture from the southeast into SoCal starting on Labor Day. Monsoon thunderstorms impacted the mountains and deserts September 2 through 5th. The event started with a nocturnal MCS over the Coachella Valley early in the morning on September 2nd, dumping 1-1.5 inches over a couple of hours. Even more thunderstorms formed Monday afternoon, especially in the mountains. Hail was reported on I-8 Monday afternoon. Storms continued each afternoon and evening in the mountains through September 5th. Some thunderstorms even reached the San Diego County coast on September 4th. Widespread outflow wind gusts of 30-45 mph were reported on the coast and in the valleys on September 4th.|At the end of September, 24-26, tropical moisture was wrapped into southern California from a closed upper low. This initially brought Santa Ana winds and very warm temperatures to the coast and on 25-26 brought scattered thunderstorms to the San Diego mountains. The flooding rains were confined to the Mojave Desert and Imperial Valley.

column37: Pleasant's Peak recorded a peak wind gust of 56 knots around 0900 PST on 10/10.
column38: High pressure over the Great Basin brought moderate Santa Ana winds to southern California October 10th and 11th. Peak wind gusts of 60-65 mph were observed in the Cajon Pass, San Bernardino, Fontana and Fremont Canyon. Peak wind gusts of 55 mph were recorded at Cuyamaca Lake and the I-8 pass in San Diego County. Most of San Diego County had wind gusts of 35-45 mph. Humidity values were in the single digits throughout much of the region. Four wildfires started during this event - two of which were impactful. The Sandalwood Fire destroyed 75 mobile homes in Redlands and the Reche Fire caused evacuations in Moreno Valley.

column38: Upper level high pressure over the Great Basin ushered in gusty Santa Ana winds, hot temperatures and single digit relative humidity. Many SoCal locations took the nation's high temperature between October 21-24. Although it was hot and dry October 21-22, winds were not very strong. The stronger winds occurred on October 24-25, where widespread wind gusts of 50-60 mph winds occurred in the mountains and passes, with isolated gusts of 70+ mph. The highest wind gust was 78 mph at Sill Hill in San Diego County. Five small fires started between October 24-25. The Miller Fire in Valley Center burned 70 acres in heavy vegetation.

column38: High pressure over the Great Basin brought high winds and single digit relative humidity to southern California. Gusty Santa Ana winds were reported in the mountains and passes, with peak gusts topping out 60-70 mph. The windiest location was Fremont Canyon at 73 mph. A few small wildfires broke out across the region. The Water Fire was the smallest, but most destructive fire during this time period, destroying 3 structures and 2 vehicles. The 46 Fire charred 300 acres and prompted the evacuations of approximately 3600 residents, with no structures destroyed or injuries reported.

column38: High pressure over the Great Basin brought weak offshore flow to southern California. Warm temperatures west of the mountains and in the deserts resulted, as well as widespread dense fog. Temperatures soared in the upper 80s to low 90s in many desert and valley communities on the 9th and 10th, with highs topping out at 94 in Anaheim, Corona and Palm Springs. Many coast and valley locations reported dense fog some nights between the 6th and 13th, where visibility was less than 1/4 mile.

column37: CalTrans reported that a vehicle spun off the road in Fallbrook and resulted in the car falling 100 feet down an embankment due to heavy rain.
column38: A closed upper low pressure system, combined with remnant tropical cyclone moisture, brought heavy rain and mountain snow to southern California. Across the area, 1 to 4 inches of rain fell, which was heaviest on the 19th and 20th. Rainfall rates of 0.50 to 1 inch per hour observed which caused impacts to many areas including Valley Center, Alpine and the Mexico border. A waterspout was spotted (photo) just west of San Clemente and Dana Point (LA waters) on the 20th, with another possible waterspout sighting on the 21st. Snow was observed down to 4200 feet.

column37: Spotter reported straight line winds and roof damage in Carlsbad from thunderstorm wind outflow on November 28th.
column38: A cold unstable upper level low pressure system from the northwest brought widespread heavy rain, thunderstorms and mountain snow to southern California over the Thanksgiving holiday. One to three feet of snow fell above 5,500 feet in the mountains, impacting highways and passes. Big Bear and Mountain High reported 30 to 48 inches total. Highway 18 was closed through December 1st. Over 40 vehicles were stuck on Highway 74 and 371, while 20 vehicles were abandoned on Highway 38. There were 10 car accidents involving snow plows. Heavy rainfall of 1 to 3 inches fell at the coast and in the valleys. San Diego River reached 9.5 feet with flooding. Numerous roadways were flooded out, especially on November 28th when the heaviest rain fell. An RV park in La Mesa flooded out due to flash flooding. The San Diego River at Fashion Valley reached 9.5 feet. 2 separate episodes of severe thunderstorms occurred in San Diego County on Thanksgiving Day.

The highest wind gust was 91 mph at Hellhole Canyon, a wind prone location in the San Diego Mountains. Many other locations had wind gusts in excess of 70 mph. A few tractor trailers were blown over on I-8 in San Diego County. Valley locations also had some gusty winds, with gusts of 25-45 mph, with locally higher gusts.

column37: Many locations across coastal San Diego County reported 1 to 1.5 inches of precipitation (2-day storm total) from December 22 through 24.
column38: A series of low pressure systems from the north and northwest, plus a weak tap into atmospheric river moisture, brought rain, mountain snow, and gusty winds to Southern California. Snow levels reached as low as 2000 feet, and brought high impact snow to locations above 4000 feet. Both I-8 through the San Diego Mountains and I-15 through the Cajon Pass were closed due to heavy snowfall. Between December 22-24, the coastal areas received 1-1.5 inches of rainfall, the valleys received 0.50-1 inch, and the mountain areas received up to 1 inch of rainfall. Again on December 26 through 27, coast and valley areas received 1 to 1.5 inches. Mountain areas received up to an inch. There were many water rescues, particularly in the Tijuana River Valley due to individuals driving through flooded roads and getting stuck. The San Diego River at Fashion Valley reached 10.5 feet on December 26.

column37: San Diego County coastal areas and valley areas received 1 to 1.5 inches between December 26 and 27. The mountain areas received up to 1 inch. There were many reports of water rescues, especially along the coast. The San Diego River at Fashion Valley reached 10.5 feet on December 26th.

column37: Sill Hill reported a peak wind gust of 56 knots around 1700 PST on December 30th.
column38: A low pressure system from the north moved into Southern California, bringing rain, mountain snow and gusty winds. The San Bernardino Mountains received a few inches of snow, heaviest overnight on the 30th. Snow Summit received 4-6 inches, Big Bear City received 4 inches, and Big Bear Lake received 2-3 inches. Winds were a big impact with this storm, especially in the mountains and passes. The Cajon Pass (I-15) had numerous big rigs overturned due to strong winds. A fatality occurred on highway 79, where the driver drove the car into a downed tree over the highway.

column37: CalTrans reported a fatality on Highway 79 near Aguanga around 0545 AM PST on December 31st. The individual drove into a downed tree across the highway. Winds are estimated to be around 40 mph at the time of the accident.

column38: Surface high pressure situated over the Great Basin brought strong north winds to Southern California on January 29th and 30th, then strong east to northeast winds on the 31st. High winds impacted the San Bernardino Mountains first with strong north winds gusting to 65 mph on the 29th and 30th. Strong winds impacted more than just the usual mountain passes and canyons; strong winds reached the Inland Empire, resulting in significant impacts. Many trees were downed on homes and cars, and one home caught fire when a tree went down on it.

column38: Surface high pressure over the Great Basin brought gusty cold Santa Ana winds to Southern California. Gusty winds occurred mainly on the 3rd and 4th, with peak gusts around 70-75 mph in the wind prone locations (passes, mountains, canyons). The dry air mass brought extreme radiational cooling to the valleys and High Desert each night. Temperatures dipped down into the mid 30s along the coast, the mid 20s to mid 30s for the valleys, and into the teens and low 20s in the High Desert.

column38: A closed upper low from the Pacific Northwest dropped south into Southern California, bringing gusty north to northeast winds, rain, and mountain snow February 9-11. Peak wind gusts of 60-70 mph were observed in the wind prone passes and canyons on February 10th and 11th. Many impacts occurred with these winds, including many overturned tractor trailers, trees downed, and flights diverted due to strong surface winds and wind shear. Rainfall totals ranged from a few tenths of an inch at the coast to up to 1 inch along the coastal slopes of the mountains. Up to 8 inches of snow fell in the San Bernardino Mountains, and up to 7 inches fell in the San Diego County mountains.

column38: A closed low pressure system tracked over northern Baja California on March 1st and 2nd, bringing rain, heavy mountain snow and high winds to Southern California. Most mountain snow fell in the San Bernardino Mountains, with up to 12-18 inches falling in the highest elevations. The Riverside and San Diego mountains also picked up a few inches of snow during this event. The highest rainfall totals were observed in the mountains, with up to 1 inch of rain. The coast and valley areas picked up around 0.10 to 0.35 inch of rain. Chain control was in effect for the San Bernardino Mountains on March 1st and 2nd. Strong winds followed behind the upper low, with wind gusts up to 65 mph observed in the mountains and passes.

column37: Gusty winds (estimated 40 mph) prevented the Coast Guard from towing in a 25-foot distressed boat to shore in Encinitas.
column38: An atmospheric river (300-400 IVT) brought widespread heavy rain to Southern California on April 6th. A few showers lingered into April 7th, but it was low impact. A warm front moved through the region on April 8th and brought waves of showers from south to north, with persistent heavy snow in the San Bernardino Mountains. Following the warm front, an upper low moved into the California Bight and stalled on April 9th, bringing 3 to 5 inches of rain to Orange County and San Diego County through the 10th. Numerous flash floods and floods occurred, especially in coastal cities. The San Diego River at Fashion Valley reached 12.5 feet (minor flood stage). Many locations recorded their highest daily rainfall record: San Diego (1.98), Chula Vista (1.56), and Vista (3.18). Oceanside Harbor recorded their wettest 24-hours on record with 3.06.

column37: Brown Field reported 1/4 mile visibility from 0400 to 0800 PST.
column38: High pressure built into Southern California on April 22nd and continued through April 30th. The deserts experienced the most extreme heat, but the coast and valleys also had multiple days with record breaking heat. Palm Springs International Airport recorded 8 days with high temperatures exceeding 101 degrees, which has not occurred since April of 1945. According to San Diego County, there were 31 heat related calls placed by residents from April 24th through the 30th, with 22 of them transported to the hospital. With onshore flow and high pressure overhead, dense fog occurred at a few coastal San Diego locations on April 25th and 26th.

column37: Areas of coastal San Diego County experienced patchy dense fog on the early mornings of May 7th and 8th. San Diego International Airport reported one quarter mile visibility on the 7th and Miramar MCAS reported a visibility near zero on the 8th.
column38: A large area of upper level high pressure over the Southwestern U.S. generated a prolonged heatwave from May 5th - 10th. Deserts were quite hot with some records broken. The high temperatures at Palm Springs International Airport were 101 degrees or higher for seven consecutive days (May 4-10). Even coastal areas got in on the warm weather, with San Diego International Airport hitting 85 degrees on May 6th. Coastal areas of San Diego County also experienced some dense fog on the mornings of the 7th and 8th. An accompanying shortwave trough brought some elevated convection bringing locally up to one quarter of an inch of rainfall on May 9th and another shortwave trough brought some windy conditions to the mountains and deserts with gusts 55-65 miles per hour on May 12th and 13th.

column37: Mesonet station HF002 Laguna Launch reports wind gust of 70 MPH at 7 PM on June 28th.
column38: An anomalously strong mid-level trough of low pressure went through Southern California and brought areas of light rain up to one quarter of an inch and some gusty winds up to 70 miles per hour in the mountains on June 28th and 29th.

column37: Stations at North Island and Imperial Beach reported intermittent dense fog with visibility as low as one quarter-mile.
column38: Areas of coastal Southern California received patchy dense fog and impactful coastal flooding in early July.

column37: One of the Navy's vessels in the San Diego Bay, the U.S.S. Bonhomme Richard, caught fire the morning of July 12th and lasted for four days. Copious amounts of smoke entered the atmosphere creating poor air quality in the greater San Diego metro, along with a total of 68 military and civilian firefighters injured during the blaze.
column38: Arson was attributed to the burning of the Navy's Bonhomme Richard ship, which lasted 4 days with over 60 injuries of navy and fire rescue personnel in the San Diego Bay.

column37: Carlsbad, San Diego, and North Island ASOS sites reported visibility of 1/4 mile at times throughout the night.
column38: Strong surface high pressure over the Desert Southwest contributed to hot conditions across Southern California for the latter part of July into early August. Many locales broke records along with places in the deserts reaching over 120 degrees at times. Some areas along the coast also reported dense fog as well.

column37: The Valley Fire started on September 5th at approximately 2:30 PM and burned approximately 16,390 acres across the southern portion of the San Diego County Mountains until being 100% contained on September 24th. Many resources were deployed with some parts of the area having evacuation orders issued.
column38: A very strong upper level high pressure became positioned over California along with an offshore flow in Southern California resulting in record very hot temperatures. September 5th and 6th were the hottest and several all-time highs were broken. The Valley and the El Dorado wildfires also started on Saturday September 5th, which scorched parts of the mountains.

column37: Areas of dense fog impacted the area with low visibility. The San Diego Airport ASOS reported dense fog at times from 10 pm Thursday to 9 am Friday, with lowest visibility of 1/8 mile.
column38: A surface area of high pressure situated over the Great Basin brought very warm conditions with gusty Santa Ana winds across the region, along with patchy dense fog nights and mornings over the coastal areas.

column37: Strong Santa Ana winds occurred in this region resulting in an 88 MPH wind gust at the Fremont Canyon RAWS station. Other notable gusts that occurred are a 66 MPH wind gust at SCE station in Trabuco Canyon and 60 MPH wind gust in the Peters Canyon area in North Tustin. Local power shutoffs occurred across the area as well.
column38: A strong Santa Ana wind event occurred across the region, producing damaging winds and the spread of two wildfires. The Blue Ridge and Silverado wildfires threatened many properties and closed down state routes and freeways for a time as well.

column37: The Silverado Fire burned 12,466 acres before being contained on November 7th around 7:08 AM. The fire burned into the city of Irvine, forcing evacuations of at least 60,000 people throughout the area. There were 5 destroyed structures along with 9 damaged. The fire also shut down State Highway 241, which burned across the road. 2 firefighters received second and third degree burns while battling the blaze.
column38: A strong Santa Ana wind event occurred across the region, producing damaging winds and the spread of two wildfires. The Blue Ridge and Silverado wildfires threatened many properties and closed down state routes and freeways for a time as well.

column37: The Blue Ridge fire started near the Green River Golf Club. The fire grew in strength rapidly over the next couple of days before being 100% contained on November 7th, burning approximately 13,964 acres. The blaze destroyed one structure and damaged ten others. Partial road closures included state routes 71, 91, 142 and 241.

column38: An upper level trough brought notable lower elevation rain and mountain snow across Southern California from November 7th - 9th. The cold nature of the system also brought chilly temperatures to the region, especially in areas of the High Desert.

column37: Areas of heavy rainfall occurred across the mountains and valleys of San Diego County. Notable totals occurred at Lake Cuyamaca with 3.98 inches of rain and Pine Valley with 3.31 inches of rain.

column38: A strong Santa Ana wind event was enhanced by a cut-off upper level low off the coast of Baja California on 19-20 January 2021. The placement of the upper level low allowed for moisture to surge into the deserts and mountains, leading to unique precipitation forecast challenges. Very strong winds combined with dry relative humidity and extremely dry fuels on the coastal mountain slopes and valleys led to several smaller scale wildfires and wind damage.

column37: Uprooted tree fell on a carport at mariners cove apartments in ocean beach, trapping several cars underneath. Extent of damage to cars unknown. Winds gusted 30-40 MPH all morning.

column37: Portions of the mountains near Mount Laguna reported gusts over 60 MPH.

column38: A passing inside slider brought gusty winds in the mountains and deserts, along with patchy fog near the coast. column38: Another series of inside sliders tracked across the Desert Southwest followed by surface high pressure over the Great Basin. This developed strong Santa Ana winds on February 24th and 25th, and then again on February 27th and 28th.

column38: A Pacific trough brought areas of heavy rainfall and mountain snow across the region on March 3rd and 4th, as well as small hail. An area of thunderstorms produced heavy rain in the San Diego metro. 22 cloud to ground lightning strikes detected.

column37: Gusty winds occurred across the mountains in excess of 70 MPH in some areas.

column37: Gusty winds occurred across the region, mostly 45-60 MPH with localized pockets of higher gusts.
column38: A West Coast trough of low pressure impacted Southern California March 9th through 13th. This storm brought periods of windy conditions across the mountains and deserts, along with widespread rain and snowfall, and areas of flooding and debris flows being observed as well.

column37: Areas of the San Diego county mountains received heavy rainfall out of this storm system, with some areas over 2 inches in total. Pine Hills reported 2.82 inches of rain.

column38: An intense area of low pressure plunged into Southern California, bringing high winds along with some wet and snowy weather.

column37: Oceanside fire reports a lightning strike started a fire. The fire was about one quarter acre and burned some surrounding vegetation and fencing near homes. No homes were burned and the crew took about an hour to mop up the scene.
column38: An area of upper-level high pressure centered over the southwestern U.S. led to well-above average temperatures across Southern California, as well as elevated thunderstorm convection. Fog along the coast caused travel disruptions.

column37: CHP and news outlets report fatal crash in Carlsbad along Interstate 5 south of Tamarak Avenue. The driver went crashed his car into the center median and was pronounced dead at the scene. Carlsbad Airport reported visibility near one quarter mile in dense fog.
column38: An area of upper-level high pressure centered over the southwestern U.S. led to well-above average temperatures across Southern California, as well as elevated thunderstorm convection. Fog along the coast caused travel disruptions.

column37: A tree fell on car and one injury reported on e avenue near 4th street in Coronado. The person had minor injuries but taken to hospital. North to northwest wind was sustained at 20-23 mph at North Island ASOS for 4 hours. Wind gusts 25 to 35 mph reported along the entire San Diego coast in the afternoon.
column38: Windy conditions across the region caused localized damage.

column37: The Southern Fire burned up to 5366 acres and reported at critical rate of spread. Westerly wind gusts of 40 mph prevented aircraft drops and fanned flames. The wildfire in shelter and mason valley caused the evacuation of up to 500 people at Butterfield Ranch Campground. 3 single family homes destroyed and 2 buildings. The wildfire began on Great Southern Overland Stage Route.
column38: Gusty westerly (onshore) winds and dry air led to the spread of wildfire on the desert slopes of the San Diego County mountains.

column37: San Diego County fire reports 7.5 acre fire that closed all four lanes along Interstate 15 South between Camino del Rey and Gopher Canyon Road. Traffic was diverted until the evening of the 23rd.

column38: A mesoscale convective system (organized thunderstorms) producing a dust storm (haboob) in the Imperial Valley, Salton Sea and Borrego deserts on the evening of August 10th. Visibility was reported as low as 1/2 mile to 1 mile observed. This was followed by hours of lightning and heavy rain in the deserts, mountains and even reaching the coast at the city of San Diego.  The system brought wind gusts 40 to 50 mph, heavy rainfall up to 2 inches in the San Diego mountains and desert slopes, and copious amounts of lightning with parts of the desert with localized flash flooding.  The southern coastal San Diego County received near one quarter of an inch.

column38: An influx of monsoonal moisture impacted portions of the southwestern U.S. from August 29th through 31st. This brought multiple thunderstorms from the deserts of Southern California all the way to the coast, where areas saw gusty winds, heavy rain, and frequent lightning. On August 30 and 31, severe thunderstorms impacted the Salton Sea and produce heavy rainfall. On August 31 a significant dust storm moved through the Coachella Valley and into the Borrego Deserts. On both days trees were reported downed in the lower Coachella Valley.

column37: A crash occurred around 1 AM in the University City area of San Diego. Just before the crash at 12:55 AM, the Miramar MCAS ASOS KNKX (2-3 SM NE of crash) reported light rain and mist with a visibility of 2.5 miles. Light rain turned heavier after 1 AM with reduced visibility as low as 1.5 miles. All southbound lanes of I-805 were shut down from 1 AM - 8 AM, when two lanes were reopened to southbound drivers. Driver appeared to avoid serious injury but the truck burst into flames and firefighters were dispatched.

column38: Tropical Cyclone Kay formed on September 4th, 2022 and made its closest approach to Southern California on the 9th and 10th, with the center of Kay coming within 120 miles of San Diego. Tropical moisture associated with Kay managed to produce heavy rainfall leading to flooding across mountainous terrain in Southern California on September 9th and 10th. This led to a number of wind damage and flooding events in the mountains and desert foothill locations in Southern California. Kay transitioned to a Post-Tropical Cyclone that weekend, but left enough lingering moisture to support additional rounds of heavy thunderstorms through the 11th and 12th of September. These later rounds of heavy rain would lead to multiple significant debris flow events in the San Bernardino County Mountains, namely in and around the Apple and El Dorado burn scars.

column38: The last in a series of atmospheric rivers impact Southern California January 14-16. Widespread heavy rainfall occurred in back-to-back two waves, with the first occurring the afternoon of January 14 into the early morning hours on January 15, and the second occurring the night of January 15 through January 16.||The first storm system resulted in numerous reports of flooding in San Diego County, Orange County and Riverside County and high-elevation snow in the mountains of San Bernardino and Riverside Counties. Rainfall amounts generally ranged from 1 to 2 inches for the coast, 1 to 2.5 inches in the valleys, 2 to 5 inches in the mountains and up to one-half of an inch in the deserts.||The second, colder system again produced widespread moderate to heavy rainfall, with the heaviest rain focusing on San Diego County. Many reports of flooding were received in San Diego County, with numerous swiftwater rescues performed, with 19 alone by San Diego City. The San Diego River overflowed, with the highest impacts reported in Fashion Valley on January 16, with a dozen swiftwater rescues performed before dawn. Nearby areas in Hotel Circle were evacuated due to the threat of flooding.||Impressive precipitation amounts were reported from the two back-to-back system, with 2 to 4 inches of rain received at the coast, 2 to 5 inches for the inland valley and 3 to 8+ inches for the mountains.

column38: Very strong Satna Ana winds impacted all of Southern California the morning of January 26. Widespread wind gusts in excess of 40 mph were reported across the coast, with wind gusts of 50 to 60 mph in the valleys and gusts over 80 mph in the mountains. Major interstate closures, including I-8 in San Diego County, and I-15 and I-215 in San Bernardino County, occurred as the result of overturned semi trucks and fallen trees and powerlines. Dozens of trees were downed and snapped in Balboa Park, including one that fell on and injured a woman, resulting in the closure of the park for the remainder of the day.

column37: Very strong winds impacted the I-8 corridor in the San Diego County Mountains the morning of January 26. Winds were gusting around 70 to 80 mph at the time of the overturned vehicles, with a peak gust of 86 mph reported at mesonet station CWDSD Crestwood.

Lightning was reported across coastal areas as well as the deserts. The heaviest rainfall occurred across the valleys where general 0.50-0.75 were reported, with the highest amount of 1.39 recorded at Harbison Canyon.
column38: A closed upper low pressure system produced light to moderate rainfall, isolated thunderstorms and light snow in the mountains February 12 to 13, with most of the impacts felt in San Diego County. The heaviest and most widespread rain occurred from the coastal slopes towards the coast in San Diego County, where isolated lightning was observed. Also, light snow was reported in the mountains in San Diego County and Riverside County.

column37: High winds occurred across the San Diego County Mountains mainly during the morning and early afternoon hours on February 14th. The Laguna Launch site recorded a peak wind gust to 93 mph, and the Volcan Mountain SDG&E site recorded a peak wind gust of 74 mph.
column38: An inslide slider storm system dove across the Western US on February 14th and 15th. This led to high winds occurring over much of the mountains and desert foothills, as well as caused snow levels to fall to around 3000-4000 feet in Southern California.

column37: Very strong winds impacted the San Diego County Mountains from the evening on February 21 through the early morning hours on February 22, when widespread wind gusts in excess of 50 mph were observed.||The following are the highest wind gusts recorded across the San Diego County Mountains:|Mesonet station VCMSD Volcan Mountain (SDGE) reported a peak wind gust of 84 mph.|Mesonet station HRPSD Harrison Park (SDGE) reported a peak wind gust of 81 mph.|Mesonet station Boulevard West (SDGE) reported a peak wind gust of 80 mph.|Pine Valley - Horse Launch reported a peak wind gust of 77 mph.|Lucky Five Ranch (SDGE) reported a peak wind gust of 75 mph.|Mesonet station DVI00558 Julian reported a peak wind gust of 70 mph.|Palomar Mountain Lookout reported a peak wind gust of 70 mph.
column38: An intense period of heavy snow and blizzard conditions, damaging winds, low-elevation snow and widespread flooding rainfall plagued Southern California February 21-27.||Very strong, and locally damaging, winds developed in the evening on February 21 and continued through February 22, especially impacting the coast and the mountains. Numerous trees were uprooted as a result of the strong winds. Temperatures plummeted on February 22 leading to low-elevation snow and cold-core thunderstorms.||The second, and highly impactful, next wave of the storm system enveloped Southern California starting on February 23. This is the period of heaviest snowfall, and a first-ever Blizzard Warning issued by NWS San Diego was in effect for the San Bernardino County Mountains. Heavy snowfall persisted through early morning on February 26, resulting in FEET of snowfall in the mountains, with many locations in the San Bernardino County Mountains seeing over 50 of snowfall. This resulted in hard closures of many highways in the San Bernardino County Mountains and left people trapped in their homes. Snow levels once again fell on February 25, with snow levels as low as 1000-2000 feet in the Inland Empire and inland Orange County. Widespread heavy thunderstorms occurred leading to local flooding, especially across San Diego County, inland Orange County and portions of the Inland Empire, as well as produced pea size hail.||The impacts of this system, especially in San Bernardino County, would be further exacerbated by an additional significant storm system that would hit only days later, leading to additional FEET of snow.

column37: A trained spotter near San Marcos reported 24hr rainfall totals of 0.95 inch.
column38: After one powerful storm struck Southern California in late February, a second storm arrived at the end of February and into early March. This second storm produced several additional feet of snow as well as high winds in the mountains, where many communities were already struggling due to snow and wind impacts from the first storm. This led to many gas leaks from failing lines that started home fires, extended road closures, numerous power outages, many downed trees, about 250 rescues from mountains in the area, as well as at least one confirmed storm-related death, and an extensive recovery process that lasted well beyond the event. About 12 persons were reported dead, though the causes of the other 11 are uncertain at this time. A Presidential Major Disaster Declaration was approved following this event.

column38: A strong atmospheric river produced widespread moderate to heavy rainfall across Southern California March 14-15. Rain fell on an extremely deep snowpack in the mountains, resulting in flooding. Flooding also occurred across the coast and valleys, where several debris flows occurred.

column38: A weak atmospheric river produced widespread moderate rainfall and high-elevation snow across Southern California March 29-30. Some isolated instances of wind damage were also observed in coastal Southern California.

column38: Monsoonal thunderstorms occurred on July 25 in the Riverside County Mountains and San Diego County Mountains. Locally heavy rainfall of 0.50-0.75 was reported in Riverside County, and a lightning strike ignited a small wildfire in San Diego County.

column37: Heavy rain associated with Tropical Cyclone Hilary impacted much of San Diego County starting late on August 19th. The heaviest rainfall occurred on August 20th which led to numerous reports of flash flooding and debris flows. Light rainfall continued through the 21st as well. The heaviest rainfall occurred in the San Diego County Mountains, where anywhere from about 3.00-6.00 of rain fell on average. Heavier amounts include 6.67 of rain at Palomar Mountain (PRMC1), 6.64 at Mount Laguna Observatory (MLGC1), and 6.08 at Ranchita (RCHC1).||Rainfall totals across the San Diego County Deserts generally ranged from 1.00-2.30. Notable totals include 2.25 of rain at San Felipe (SFVC1), 2.20 of rain at Anza Borrego Desert Park (UCAB), and 1.55 of rain at Ocotillo Wells (OCWC1).||Rainfall totals across the San Diego County Valleys ranged from 1.50-3.60. Notable totals from this region include 3.56 of rain at Valley Center (CW9939), 3.51 at Lake Wohlford (WHLC1), 3.47 of rain in Fallbrook, 3.10 of rain in Escondido (EW6576), 2.42 in Poway (CA-SD-12), and 2.23 in Ramona (CA-SD-186).||Rainfall totals across the San Diego County coastal and beach areas generally ranged from 1.50-3.25. column38: Tropical Storm Hilary made landfall across northern Baja California on August 20, and moved through Southern California that afternoon and evening. Torrential rainfall occurred across mountain and desert communities, resulting in catastrophic flash flooding and debris flows, damaged railways and bridges, and the closing of major interstates including I-8 in San Diego County and I-10 in Riverside County. Widespread tropical-storm force winds were recorded across much of Southern California.

column37: Dense fog reducing visibility to as low as 1/4 SM occurring from roughly 3:50 AM to 9:00 AM PDT caused numerous delays at San Diego International Airport.
column38: An upper level area of high pressure caused very hot daytime temperatures to occur in late August 2023. It also caused the daily marine layer low clouds/fog to become more confined to the coast, which resulted in dense fog impacting San Diego International Airport for an extended period of time, resulting in a large number of delays.

Several reports of street and flash flooding were also received across areas from the coast to as far east as Anza-Borrego State Park.

column37: An eucalyptus tree was blown over and blocked all lanes on Sweetwater Road in Bonita. Wind gusts of 30-35 mph were recorded at the time. Severe trees were downed along I-805 and required emergency clean up by Caltrans. Strong winds from a thunderstorm.
column38: Historic flooding occurred on January 22nd. Heavy rainfall occurred between 8 am and noon across western San Diego county. The heaviest rainfall occurred between 9 am and 11 am in the east side of the city of San Diego in Encanto and Lemon Grove to Spring Valley. Rainfall rates were observed at 1.5 to 2.5 inches in 60 minutes and resulted in 1000 year return intervals. Over 200 water rescues at homes, streets and in water channels were performed by San Diego Fire and Rescue. FEMA found 1000 homes damaged in the following weeks and 600 were declared major damage resulting in up to 31 million in damage claims and displaced residents, including 1200 households, in temporary shelters for several months. San Diego County EOC was activated on January 22 and remained activated at a low level into May 2024. The areas flooded the most were Mountain View, Encanto, Valencia Park, Shelltown, Southcrest, and Lincoln Park.

column37: Heavy rain fell across much of San Diego County on February 1st and 2nd. Rainfall totals generally ranged from 1.00-3.00 inches, with totals between 3.50-4.25 inches occurring in portions of the San Diego County Mountains near Palomar Mountain.
column38: An atmospheric river impacted Southern California on February 1st. Impacts were felt across much of the region, but the most notable impacts were near the Seal Beach area. Several reports of flooding leading to road closures were received from this area.

column37: Back-to-back atmospheric river events impacted San Diego County starting early on February 4th, with weather impacts occurring through much of the week, and finally ending on February 9th. Much of San Diego County received anywhere from 1.50-5.00 inches of rainfall. Coastal areas generally received 2-4 of rain including 2.85 at San Diego International Airport, 3.93 in Escondido, and between 4.00-4.50 near the Oceanside and Carlsbad areas. Mountainous areas received generally 2-7 of rain, while the deserts generally received between 0.15 and 0.90 of rain. Some notable localized higher totals include 8.27 at the San Onofre (SOFC1) site, 7.17 at the Lake Cuyamaca (CYDC1) site, 6.96 at the Camp Trgt Range RAWS (CTGC1) site, and 5.85 at the CPEN Fallbrook RAWS site (FBZC1).
column38: An atmospheric river took aim at Southern California for several days starting early on February 4th, with impacts lasting through February 9th. Over a foot of rain fell in some locations, while some areas in the mountains received several feet of accumulating snow, depending on elevation.

column37: Heavy rain fell across San Diego County on March 2. The mountains saw accumulations of 0.50-2.50, while lower elevations across the coast and valleys saw 0.25-1.00, with locally higher amounts. The lower deserts saw minimal accumulations.
column38: Strong Winds and Widespread Precipitation Impact Southern California on March 2. The strongest winds were reported in the mountains and along the desert slopes, where gusts over 70 mph occurred. Widely beneficial precipitation fell, but reports of flooding were received in the San Bernardino County Mountains.

column37: High winds impacted the San Diego County Deserts on March 23rd. Peak wind gusts were generally in the 35-45 mph range. Some notable higher gusts include 60 mph at Anza Borrego State Park.
column38: An active month continued on March 23-24, as another storm system brought more precipitation impacts to Southern California. The main impacts were in the form of snow at some mountain communities.

column37: High winds impacted the San Diego County Mountains on March 30th. Peak wind gusts were generally in the 35-50 mph range. Some notable higher gusts include 61 mph at Palomar Mountain Lookout, and 58 mph at the Harrison Park SDGE site.
column38: A strong low pressure system and an associated atmospheric river impacted Southern California on March 30th and 31st. This event saw impacts in the forms of heavy rain, some scattered thunderstorms, and snow to mountain communities above 5000 feet in elevation.

column37: East Warners SDGE site had a gust to 50 mph at at 1220 pm PDT on July 24.
column38: Several wildfires erupted in July, mainly late in the month. Hawarden fire in City of Riverside did the most damage.  The excessive heat caused rapid drying of the vegetation and fuels.

column37: Grove wildfire started around 1 pm PDT on July 25, 2024. About 900 acres was burned. Lightning occurred in the area and was suspected to cause the wildfire. State route 79 was closed by Highway Patrol.

column37: Shockey Truck Trail SGDE measured wind gust 51 mph. Temperature dropped from 102F to 76F following thunderstorm outflow.

column37: Pine Valley Horse mesonet reported gusts 53 mph from thunderstorms along Interstate 8.

column37: Thunderstorms over the Laguna mountains of  San Diego county near Pine Valley on August 1, 2024. 0.44 reported at Cameron Fire station and 0.48 at Japatul fire station. This is along and south of I-8.
column38: A few thunderstorms with heavy rain occurred early August. The Nixon wildfire also erupted.

column37: San Diego city Mission Beach lifeguards reported dense fog 1/4 SM visibility.
column38: During a heat wave dense fog from a very shallowed lowered marine layer occurred August 6 to 7, 2024.

column37: San Diego airport reported 1/4SM fog at 0600 August 7, 2024.  North Island Coronado reported 1/4SM fog at the same time.
column38: During a heat wave dense fog from a very shallowed lowered marine layer occurred August 6 to 7, 2024.

column37: Thunderstorm wind gusts at Hoskings Ranch SDGE weather station. Also 1.25 inches rainfall at VCNC1 station.  Persistent thunderstorms for up to 2 inches.
column38: A monsoon surge occurred on Sunday August 11, 2024. Numerous strong to severe thunderstorms erupted across the San Diego mountains and into the Riverside County mountains. Thunderstorms produced hail, wind gusts and rainfall rates of 1 inch in 60 minutes.

column37: Rainfall of 2.54 inches in about 2 hours was recorded at the Mason Valley mesonet along S2 highway in the San Diego Deserts. Radar estimates as high as 3.50 inches.

column37: Lucky Five SDGE weather station recorded a thunderstorm wind gust of 43 mph at 240 pm August 11, 2024.

column37: Tenaja wildfire burned around 100 acres.  This is just south of SR 74.
column38: Several brush and wildfire erupted due to severely dry conditions in August.

column37: Keys fire in Valley Center resulted in evacuations. Old Lilac road and Keys Creek road. Wildfire was just over 50 acres.
column38: A few more wildfires occurred due to dry vegetation and the much above average temperatures in July and August for inland areas.
